digo-slate-a-us-based-digital-agency-1027408046|title=Zensar Acquires Indigo Slate, a US Based Digital Agency {{!}} Markets Insider|work=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052548/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/zensar-acquires-indigo-slate-a-us-based-digital-agency-1027408046|archive-date=4 September 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Locations==\nZensar has offices in eighteen countries.<ref name = >{{cite web | url = https://www.vccircle.com/zensar-to-divest-india-middle-east-and-australia-businesses/ | publisher = VC Circle | title =  Zensar to divest India, Middle East and Australia businesses| accessdate = 20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{nowrap|List of subsidiaries}}\n|-\n! Name !! Location\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies UK Ltd. || United Kingdom\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies B.V. || Geneva\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies B.V. || The Netherlands\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies Keizersgracht || The Netherlands\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies Herriotstra\u00dfe || Frankfurt, Germany\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies Regus Business Centre GmbH || Austria\n|-\n| Zensar Technologies, Inc. || United States of America\n|-\n| Zensar (Africa) Holdings (Pty) Ltd.|| Johannesburg\n|-\n|}\n\n== Reception == \nZensar was the innovation award winner in the \"Creating an Impact-IT Skills\" category at India Perspectives 2018. Garner [[Magic Quadrant]] named the company Niche Player 2019 for [[managed mobility services]].<ref name = gartner>{{cite web | url = https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-cm/zensar-named-niche-player-in-2019-gartner-magic-quadrant-for-managed-mobility-services-global-119072501224_1.html | publisher = Business Standard | title = Zensar named Niche Player in 2019 Gartner Magic Quadrant for Managed Mobility Services, Global  | accessdate = 20 March 2020}}</ref> The company is often quoted by analysts in [[Trade magazine | industry media]] for its expertise on enterprise IT spending, [[research]] [[consulting]] and [[advisory]] [[services]].<ref name = yahoonews>{{cite web | url = https://finance.yahoo.com/news/30-earnings-growth-did-zensar-001814300.html | publisher = Yahoo! News | title = With 30% Earnings Growth, Did Zensar Technologies Limited Outperform The Industry?| accessdate = 27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public listed software companies of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.zensar.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zensar}}\n[[Category:1991 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Pune]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1991]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Information technology consulting firms of India]]\n[[Category:RPG Group]]\n[[Category:Software companies of India]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:advisory\u2192Consultant", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zensar_Technologies"}
{"title_page": "Iraqi Army", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{update|date=October 2017}}\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Iraqi Army\n| native_name = \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0629 \n|image= Iraqi Ground Forces Emblem.svg\n|image_size= 160px\n|caption= Iraqi Ground Forces' insignia\n|start_date={{Start date|1921}}\n|active =\n|country= {{flag|Iraq}}\n|role= Ground-based military warfare\n|type= [[Army]]\n|size= Active: 54,000<ref>[[International Institute for Strategic Studies]], The Military Balance 2019, 344.</ref>\n|command_structure= [[Ministry of Defence (Iraq)|Iraqi Ministry of Defense]]\n|garrison= [[Baghdad]], Iraq\n|garrison_label=\n|motto=\n|march=\n|battles= '''First incarnation''':<br>[[Anglo-Iraqi War]]<br />[[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]]<br />[[First Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War]]<br />[[Six-Day War]]<br />[[Yom Kippur War]]<br />[[Second Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War]]<br />[[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]<br />[[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]<br />[[Iraq War]]<br />'''Second incarnation''':<br>Iraq War<br />[[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]<br />[[2017 Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]]<br />[[Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)]]<br />[[Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)]]<br />[[Military intervention against ISIL]]\n| anniversaries=January 6<ref>{{cite book|title=Iraq's Armed Forces: An Analytical History |url=https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma |url-access=registration |last=Al-Marashi |first=Ibrahim |author2=Sammy Salama |year=2008 |publisher=Routledge |location=London and New York |isbn=0-415-40078-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma/page/206 206]}} Al-Marashi and Salama note that the eighty-third anniversary of Iraqi Army Day was celebrated in 2004.</ref>\n| decorations=\n| nickname = \n| battle_honours=\n| disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1=\n| commander1_label=\n| commander2=\n| commander2_label=\n| notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol=\n| identification_symbol_label=\n| identification_symbol_2= [[File:Flag of the Iraqi Ground Forces.svg|border|100px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label= Flag\n}}\n\nThe '''Iraqi Army''', officially the '''Iraqi Ground Forces''' ([[Arabic]]: \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0629), is the ground force component of the [[Iraqi Armed Forces]], having been active in various incarnations throughout the 20th and 21st centuries. It was known as the '''Royal Iraqi Army''' up until the coup of July 1958.\n\nThe Iraqi Army in its modern form was first created by the [[United Kingdom]] during the [[Interwar period|inter-war period]] of ''de facto'' British control of [[Mandatory Iraq]]. Following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq by U.S. forces]] in 2003, the Iraqi Army was rebuilt along American lines with enormous amounts of U.S. military assistance at every level. Because of the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]] that began shortly after the invasion, the Iraqi Army was later designed to initially be a counter-insurgency force.<ref name=mssiaug06>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|title=Measuring Security and Stability in Iraq|work=U.S. Department of Defense|date=August 2006|page=52|access-date=2007-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911200618/http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|archive-date=2007-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://csis.org/files/publication/100422_GulfMilBal.pdf|title=The Gulf Military Balance in 2010|publisher=[[Center for Strategic and International Studies]]|date=22 April 2010|page=2|access-date=3 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809080759/http://csis.org/files/publication/100422_GulfMilBal.pdf|archive-date=9 August 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|withdrawal of U.S. troops]] in 2010,  Iraqi forces have assumed full responsibility for their own security.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/15/iraq-withdrawal-us-troops_n_1012661.html|title=Iraq Withdrawal: U.S. Abandoning Plans To Keep Troops In Country|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=15 October 2011|access-date=24 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230100328/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/15/iraq-withdrawal-us-troops_n_1012661.html|archive-date=30 December 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' article suggested that, between 2004 and 2014, the U.S. had provided the Iraqi Army with $25 billion in training and equipment in addition to an even larger sum from the Iraqi treasury.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/world/middleeast/graft-hobbles-iraqs-military-in-fighting-isis.html?emc=edit_th_20141124&nl=todaysheadlines&nlid=68502098&_r=0|title=Graft Hobbles Iraq's Military In Fighting Isis|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 November 2014|access-date=22 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013223849/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/world/middleeast/graft-hobbles-iraqs-military-in-fighting-isis.html?emc=edit_th_20141124&nl=todaysheadlines&nlid=68502098&_r=0|archive-date=13 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Army extensively collaborated with Iraqi [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] during anti-ISIL operations.\n\n==History==\nThe threat of war with newly forming [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]], which claimed the Ottoman [[Mosul Province, Ottoman Empire|vilayet of Mosul]] as part of their country, led the British to form the Iraqi Army on 6 January 1921. The Mussa Al-Kadhum Brigade consisted of ex-Iraqi-Ottoman officers, whose barracks were located in [[Kadhimyah]].{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=149}} The United Kingdom provided support and training to the Iraqi Army and the Iraqi Air Force through a small military mission based in [[Baghdad]].<ref>Lyman, p. 25</ref> Iraqi Army Day celebrates the soldiers that fight for Iraq.\n\n===Royal Iraqi Army===\n{{Main|Kingdom of Iraq}}\nFrom 1533 to 1918, [[Ottoman Iraq|Iraq]] was under the rule of the [[Ottoman Empire]], and fought as part of the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire]]. After 1917, the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] took control of the country. The first Iraqi military forces established by the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] were the [[Iraq Levies]], several battalions of troops tasked to guard the [[Royal Air Force]] ([[RAF]]) bases from which the British controlled Iraq.\n\nIn August 1921, the British installed [[Hashemite]] [[King of Iraq|King]] [[Faisal I of Iraq|Faisal I]] as the client ruler of the [[Mandatory Iraq|British Mandate of Iraq]]. Faisal had been forced out as the [[King of Syria]] by the [[French Third Republic|French]]. Likewise, British authorities selected [[Sunni]] Arab elites from the region for appointments to government and ministry offices in Iraq. The British and the Iraqis formalized the relationship between the two nations with the [[Anglo-Iraqi Treaty|Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1922]]. With Faisal's ascension to the throne, the Iraqi Army became the Royal Iraqi Army (RIrA).\n\nIn 1922, the army totalled 3,618 men. This was well below the 6,000 men requested by the Iraqi monarchy and even less than the British set limit of 4,500. Unattractive salaries hindered early recruiting efforts. At this time, the United Kingdom maintained the right to levy local forces like the British-officered [[Iraq Levies]] which were under direct British control. With a strength of 4,984 men, the Iraq Levies outnumbered the army with its British set limit of 4,500 men.\n\nIn 1924, the army grew to 5,772 men and, by the following year, had grown still more to reach 7,500 men. It was to stay at 7,500 men until 1933. The force now had six infantry battalions, three cavalry regiments, two mountain regiments, and one field battery.<ref>Al-Marashi, pp. 23\u201324</ref>\n\nIn 1932, the [[Kingdom of Iraq]] was granted official independence. This was in accordance with the [[Anglo-Iraqi Treaty (1930)|Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1930]], whereby the [[United Kingdom]] would end its official mandate on the condition that the Iraqi government would allow British advisers to take part in government affairs, allow British military bases to remain, and a requirement that Iraq assist the United Kingdom in wartime.<ref>Ghareeb, Edmund A.; Dougherty, Beth K. ''Historical Dictionary of Iraq''. Lanham, Maryland and Oxford: The Scarecrow Press, Ltd., 2004. Pp. lvii.</ref>\n\nUpon achieving independence in 1932, political tensions arose over the continued British presence in Iraq, with Iraq's government and politicians split between those considered pro-British and those who were considered anti-British. The pro-British faction was represented by politicians such as [[Nuri as-Said]] who did not oppose a continued British presence. The anti-British faction was represented by politicians such as [[Rashid Ali al-Gaylani]] who demanded that remaining British influence in the country be removed.<ref name=\"Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lvii\">Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lvii</ref> In 1936, General [[Bakr Sidqi]], who had won a reputation from suppressing tribal revolts, was named Chief of the General Staff and successfully pressured the King to demand that the Cabinet resign.<ref>S.E. Finer, The Man on Horseback, 1962, 157-8.</ref> From that year to 1941, five coups by the RIrA occurred during each year led by the chief officers of the army against the government to pressure the government to concede to Army demands.<ref name=\"Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lvii\" />\n\n=== 1941 coup ===\n{{Main|1941 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat}}\nIn early April 1941, during [[World War II]], Rashid Ali al-Gaylani and members of the anti-British \"[[Golden Square (Iraq)|Golden Square]]\" launched a [[1941 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat|''coup d'\u00e9tat'' against the current government]].  [[List of Prime Ministers of Iraq|Prime Minister]] [[Taha al-Hashimi]] resigned and Rashid Ali al-Gaylani took his place as Prime Minister.  Rashid Ali also proclaimed himself chief of a \"National Defence Government.\"  He did not overthrow the monarchy, but installed a more compliant [[Regent]].  He also attempted to restrict the rights of the British which were granted them under the 1930 treaty.\n\nOn April 30 Iraqi Army units took the high ground to the south of [[RAF Habbaniya]]. An Iraqi envoy was sent to demand that no movements, either ground or air, were to take place from the base. The British refused the demand and then themselves demanded that the Iraqi units leave the area at once. In addition, the British landed forces at [[Basra]] and the Iraqis demanded that these forces be removed.\n\nAt 0500 hours on 2 May 1941, the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]] broke out between the British and Rashid Ali's new government when the British at [[RAF Habbaniya]] launched [[air strikes]] against the Iraqis. By this time, the army had grown significantly. It had four infantry divisions with some 60,000 men.<ref>Playfair, I.S.O.; and others (2006). The Mediterranean and Middle East, Volume II The Germans come to the help of their Ally (1941). History of the Second World War, United Kingdom Military Series, Official Campaign History, Naval & Military Press. {{ISBN|1-84734-427-5}}, p.182 and Lyman, ''Iraq 1941'', p. 25</ref> At full strength, each division had three brigades. The Iraqi [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st]] and [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Divisions]] were stationed in Baghdad. Also based within Baghdad was the Independent Mechanized Brigade comprising a [[L3/35]] light tank company, an [[Crossley Motors|armoured car company]], two battalions of [[motorized infantry|\"mechanized\" infantry]] transported in trucks, a \"mechanized\" machine-gun company, and a \"mechanized\" artillery brigade. The [[2nd Division (Iraq)|2nd Division]] was stationed in [[Kirkuk]], and the 4th Division was in [[Al Diwaniyah]], on the main rail line from Baghdad to Basra. All these \"mechanized\" infantry units were transported by trucks.\n\nHostilities between the British and the Iraqis lasted from 2 May to 30 May 1941. The German government despatched an aviation unit, [[Fliegerf\u00fchrer Irak]], and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] send limited assistance, but both were too late and far from adequate. In the end, the British were able to march on [[Baghdad]] and Rashid Ali al-Gaylani fled.\n\nAfter the Anglo-Iraqi War ended, Nuri as-Said returned as Prime Minister and dominated the politics of Iraq until the overthrow of the monarchy and his assassination in 1958. Nuri as-Said pursued a largely pro-[[Western world|western policy]] during this period.<ref>Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lviii</ref> The army was not disbanded. Instead, it was maintained to hinder possible German offensive actions launched from southern [[RSFSR|Russia]]. British troops left in the late 1940s.\n\n=== 1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War ===\nIn the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], the Iraqis deployed an expeditionary force which peaked at 15,000\u201318,000 men.{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=150, 156}} In 1948, the army deployed 21,000 men in twelve brigades and the [[Iraqi Air Force|Royal Iraqi Air Force]] deployed 100 planes, mostly British. Initially the Iraqis committed around 3,000<ref>D. Kurzman, ''Genesis 1948'', 1972, p. 382.</ref> men to the war effort including four infantry brigades, one armoured battalion and support personnel. These forces were to operate under Jordanian guidance<ref>I. Pappe, ''The Ethnic Cleansing of Palestine'', 2006, p. 129.</ref> During the first truce the Iraqis increased their force to about 10,000.<ref>Kurzman, p. 556.</ref> Ultimately, the Iraqi expeditionary force numbered around 15,000 to 18,000 men.{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=150}}\n\nThe first Iraqi forces to be deployed reached Jordan in April 1948 under the command of General [[Nur ad-Din Mahmud]]. On 15 May, Iraqi engineers built a [[pontoon bridge]] across the Jordan River and attacked the Israeli settlement of [[Gesher, Israel|Gesher]]. Over 3,000 Iraqi soldiers with armor and air support were unable to defeat less than 50 lightly armed Jewish defenders. Following this defeat Iraqi forces moved into the [[Nablus]]\u2013[[Jenin]]\u2013[[Tulkarm]] strategic triangle, where they suffered heavy casualties in the Israeli attack on Jenin which began on 3 June, but they managed to hold on to their positions. Active Iraqi involvement in the war effectively ended at this point.{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=149\u2013155}}\n\nIn May 1955 the British finally withdrew from Iraq. The Iraqi authorities said during the withdrawal negotiations that a motorised infantry brigade was to be formed, based at the previous [[RAF Habbaniya]], a location that had been occupied by the British [[Iraq Levies]].<ref>Solomon (Sawa) Solomon, [http://www.edessa.com/history/solmn1.htm \"The Assyrian Levies, The Final Chapter\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722133011/http://www.edessa.com/history/solmn1.htm |date=2011-07-22 }}, ''Nineveh Magazine'' 4Q,93, V16, No4.</ref>\n\n===Republic declared===\n{{Main|Iraqi Republic (1958\u201368)}}\n\nThe [[Hashemite monarchy]] lasted until 1958, when it was overthrown through a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] by the Iraqi Army, known as the [[14 July Revolution]]. King [[Faisal II of Iraq]] along with members of the royal family were murdered. The coup brought [[Abd al-Karim Qasim]] to power. He withdrew from the [[Baghdad Pact]] and established friendly relations with the [[Soviet Union]].\n\nWhen Q\u0101sim distanced himself from [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Abd an-N\u0101sir]], he faced growing opposition from pro-Egypt officers in the Iraqi army. `Arif, who wanted closer cooperation with Egypt, was stripped of his responsibilities and thrown in prison. When the garrison in [[Mosul]] rebelled against Q\u0101sim's policies, he allowed the Kurdish leader [[Mustafa Barzani|Barz\u0101n\u012b]] to return from exile in the Soviet Union to help suppress the pro-N\u0101sir rebels.\n\nThe creation of the new Fifth Division, consisting of mechanized infantry, was announced on 6 January 1959, [[Army Day]].<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 'New Division for Iraq Army,' 7 January 1959</ref> Q\u0101sim was also promoted to the rank of general.\n\nIn 1961, an Army buildup close to [[Kuwait]] in conjunction with Iraqi claims over the small neighbouring state, led to a crisis with British military forces ([[British army|land]], [[Royal Navy|sea]], and [[Royal Air force|air]]) deployed to Kuwait for a period. In 1961, [[Kuwait]] gained independence from Britain and Iraq claimed sovereignty over Kuwait. As in the 1930s, Qasim based Iraq's claim on the assertion that Kuwait had been a district of the Ottoman province of Basra, unjustly severed by the British from the main body of Iraqi state when it had been created in the 1920s.<ref>Tripp, Charles. ''A History of Iraq''. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 2002, p.165</ref> Britain reacted strongly to Iraq's claim and sent troops to Kuwait to deter Iraq. Q\u0101sim was forced to back down and in October 1963, Iraq recognized the sovereignty of Kuwait.\n\nQ\u0101sim was assassinated in February 1963, when the [[Ba'ath Party]] [[February 1963 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat|took power]] under the leadership of General [[Ahmed Hasan al-Bakr]] ([[Prime Minister of Iraq|prime minister]]) and Colonel [[Abdul Salam Arif]] ([[President of Iraq|president]]). Nine months later `Abd as-Salam Muhammad `Arif led a successful coup against the Ba'ath government. On 13 April 1966, President Abdul Salam Arif died in a helicopter crash and was succeeded by his brother, General [[Abdul Rahman Arif]]. Following the [[Six-Day War]] of 1967, the Ba'ath Party felt strong enough to retake power (17 July 1968). Ahmad Hasan al-Bakr became president and chairman of the Revolutionary Command Council (RCC).\n\n===Six-Day War===\n[[File:Iraqi AML-60-20.jpg|thumb|Iraqi Army [[Panhard AML|Panhard AML-60]] armored car, 1970s. Iraq ordered about 250 of these vehicles between 1968 and 1976.]]\nDuring the Six-Day War, the Iraqi [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Armoured Division]] was deployed in eastern Jordan.<ref>Pollack, 2002, p.167</ref> However, the Israeli attack against the West Bank unfolded so quickly that the Iraqi force could not organise itself and reach the front before Jordan ceased fighting. Repeated Israeli airstrikes also held them up so that by the time they did reach the [[Jordan River]] the entire [[West Bank]] was in Israeli hands. During the course of the [[Jordanian campaign (1967)|Jordanian Campaign]] ten Iraqis were killed and 30 Iraqis were wounded, especially as the main battle was in Jerusalem. Fighting also raged in other areas of the West Bank, where Iraqi commandos and Jordanian soldiers defended their positions.<ref>Follow me- The story of the Six Day War 2. Six Day War- Tom Segev</ref>\n\nBarz\u0101n\u012b and the Kurds who had begun a rebellion in 1961 were still causing problems in 1969. The secretary-general of the Ba`th party, [[Saddam Hussein]], was given responsibility to find a solution. It was clear that it was impossible to defeat the Kurds by military means and in 1970 a political agreement was reached between the rebels and the Iraqi government.\n\nFollowing the Arab defeat in 1967, Jordan became a hotbed of Palestinian activity. During this time PLO elements attempted to create a Palestinian state within Jordan caused the Jordanians to launch their full military force against the PLO. As they were doing this Syria invaded Jordan and Iraq moved a brigade in Rihab, Jordan.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} Otherwise the only Iraqi activity was that they fired upon some Jordanian aircraft.\n\nIraq sent a 60,000 man expeditionary force to the Syrian front during the [[Yom Kippur War]]. It consisted of the 3rd and [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Armoured Divisions]], two infantry brigades, twelve artillery battalions, and a special forces brigade. The two armoured divisions were, Pollack says, 'unquestionably the best formations of the Iraqi Army.'(Pollack p.&nbsp;167) Yet during their operations on the Golan Heights, their performance was awful in virtually every category of military effectiveness. Military intelligence, initiative, and small unit independent action was virtually absent.<ref>Pollack p.173-5, citing among others Tzvi Ofer, 'The Iraqi Army in the Yom Kippur War,' transl. 'Hatzav,' Tel Aviv: Ma'arachot, 1986, p.128-65. Pollack notes that the various accounts of Iraqi operations on the Golan Heights are highly contradictory. He relies on Ofer, 1986, which is an Israeli General Staff critique of the official Iraqi General Staff analysis of the battle.</ref>\n\nAfter the war, Iraq started a major military build-up. Active duty manpower doubled, and so did number of divisions, from six to twelve, of which four were now armoured and two mechanised infantry. (Pollack p.&nbsp;182)\n\n===Iran\u2013Iraq war===\n{{see also|Order of battle during the Iran\u2013Iraq War}}\nLater, Saddam Hussein, looking to build fighting power against Iran soon after the outbreak of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]] doubled the size of the Iraqi army from 1981, when it numbered 200,000 soldiers in 12 divisions and 3 independent brigades, to 1985, when it had 500,000 men in 23 divisions and nine brigades. The first new divisions were created in 1981 when the 11th and 12th Border Guard Divisions were converted into infantry formations and the 14th Infantry Division was formed.<ref>Pollack 2002 p.&nbsp;207</ref> Yet the rise in number of divisions is misleading, because during the war Iraqi divisions abandoned a standard organisation with permanent ('organic') brigades assigned to each division. Instead division headquarters were assigned a mission or sector and then assigned brigades to carry out the task - up to eight to ten brigades on some occasions.<ref>Pollack 2002 p.&nbsp;208</ref>\n\nThe war came at a great cost in lives and economic damage - a half a million Iraqi and Iranian soldiers as well as civilians are believed to have died in the war with many more injured and wounded - but brought neither reparations nor change in borders. The conflict is often compared to [[World War I]],<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''A History of Modern Iran'', Cambridge, 2008, p.171</ref> in that the tactics used closely mirrored those of the 1914\u20131918 war, including large scale [[trench warfare]], manned machine-gun posts, bayonet charges, use of [[barbed wire]] across trenches and on [[no-mans land]], [[human wave attacks]] by Iran, and Iraq's extensive use of [[chemical weapons]] (such as [[mustard gas]]) against Iranian [[troops]] and [[civilians]] as well as [[Halabja chemical attack|Iraqi Kurds]].\n\n===Invasion of Kuwait and the Persian Gulf War===\nBy the eve of the [[Invasion of Kuwait]] which led to the 1991 [[Persian Gulf War]], the army was estimated to number 1,000,000 men.<ref>Brassey's, [[IISS]] Military Balance 1989-90, p.101</ref> Just before the [[Persian Gulf War]] began, the force comprised 47 infantry divisions plus 9 armoured and mechanised divisions, grouped in 7 corps.<ref name=\"Michael Eisenstadt 1993, p.124\">Michael Eisenstadt, 'The Iraqi Armed Forces Two Years On, [[Jane's Intelligence Review]], March 1993, p.124</ref> This gave a total of about 56 army divisions, and total land force divisions reached 68 when the 12 [[Iraqi Republican Guard]] divisions were included.<ref>Eisenstadt notes that four IRG security divisions were formed between the invasion of Kuwait and the outbreak of war. They remained in Iraq during the war. Eisenstadt p.124</ref> Although it was said at the time in Western media{{Which|date=July 2018}} that Iraqi troops numbered approximately 545,000 (even 600,000) today some think<ref>Friedman, \"Desert Victory,\" USNI, 1992, 443, 446.</ref> that both the qualitative and quantitative descriptions of the Iraqi army at the time were exaggerated, as they included both temporary and auxiliary support elements. Many{{How many|date=July 2018}} of the Iraqi troops were also young, under-resourced and poorly trained [[conscript]]s. Saddam did not trust the army; among counterbalancing security forces was the [[Iraqi Popular Army]].\n\n[[File:Demolished vehicles line Highway 80 on 18 Apr 1991.jpg|thumb|left|Demolished Iraqi vehicles line the [[Highway of Death]] on 18 April 1991.]]\nThe wide range of suppliers of Iraqi equipment resulted in a lack of standardization in this large heterogeneous force. It additionally suffered from poor training and poor motivation. The majority of Iraqi armoured forces still used old Chinese [[Type 59 tank|Type 59s]] and [[Type 69]]s, Soviet-made [[T-55]]s & [[T-62]]s from the 1950s and 1960s, and some [[T-72]]s from the 1970s in 1991. These machines were not equipped with up-to-date equipment, such as [[thermal sight]]s or [[laser rangefinder]]s, and their effectiveness in modern combat was very limited. The Iraqis failed to find an effective countermeasure to the thermal sights and the [[kinetic energy round|sabot rounds]] used by the [[M1 Abrams]], [[Challenger 1 tank|Challenger 1]] and the other Coalition tanks. This equipment enabled Coalition M1A1s to effectively engage and destroy Iraqi tanks from well outside the distance (e.g. 8,200&nbsp;ft to Iraqi ranges of 6,600&nbsp;ft) that Iraqi tanks could engage.\n\nThe Iraqi tank crews used old, cheap steel [[Kinetic energy penetrator|penetrators]]{{Which|date=July 2018}} against the advanced [[Chobham Armour]] of these US and British tanks, with disastrous results{{Clarify|reason=What were the results?|date=July 2018}}. The Iraqi forces also failed to utilize the advantage that could be gained from using [[urban warfare]]&nbsp;\u2014 fighting within [[Kuwait City]]&nbsp;\u2014 which could have inflicted significant casualties on the attacking forces. Urban combat reduces the range at which fighting occurs and can negate some of the technological advantage that well equipped forces enjoy. Iraqis also tried to use [[Military doctrine#Russia and the Soviet Union|Soviet military doctrine]], but the implementation failed due to the lack of skill of their commanders and the preventive air strikes of the [[USAF]] and [[RAF]] on communication centers and bunkers.\n\nWhile the exact number of Iraqi combat casualties has yet to be firmly determined, sources agree that the losses were substantial. Immediate estimates said up to 100,000 Iraqis were killed. More recent estimates indicate that Iraq probably sustained between 20,000 and 35,000 fatalities, though other figures still maintain fatalities could have been as high as 200,000.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Robert Fisk, ''The Great War For Civilisation; The Conquest of the Middle East'' (Fourth Estate, 2005), p.853.</ref> A report commissioned by the U.S. Air Force, estimated 10,000-12,000 Iraqi combat deaths in the air campaign and as many as 10,000 casualties in the ground war.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Keaney |first=Thomas |author2=Eliot A. Cohen |title=Gulf War Air Power Survey |publisher=United States Dept. of the Air Force |year=1993 |location=|isbn=0-16-041950-6}}</ref> This analysis is based on Iraqi prisoner of war reports. It is known{{By whom|date=July 2018}} that between 20,000 and 200,000 Iraqi soldiers were killed. According to the Project on Defense Alternatives study,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0310rm8ap2.html|title=Wages of War - Appendix 2: Iraqi Combatant and Noncombatant Fatalities in the 1991 Gulf War<!-- Bot generated title -->|access-date=2009-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416233846/http://www.comw.org/pda/0310rm8ap2.html|archive-date=2009-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> 3,664 Iraqi civilians and between 20,000 and 26,000 military personnel were killed in the conflict. 75,000 Iraqi soldiers were wounded in the fighting.\n\n===During the 1990s===\nThe [[International Institute for Strategic Studies]] ([[IISS]]) estimated the army's composition immediately after the 1991 War as 6 'armoured'/'mechanised' divisions, 23 infantry divisions, 8 Republican Guard divisions and four Republican Guard internal security divisions.<ref>[[IISS]] Military Balance 1992-3</ref> [[Jane's Defence Weekly]] for 18 July 1992 stated that 10,000 troops from 5 divisions were fighting against Shia Muslims in the southern marshlands.\n\nThe IISS gave the Iraqi Army's force structure as of 1 July 1997 as seven Corps headquarters, six armoured or mechanised divisions, 12 infantry divisions, 6 RGF divisions, four [[Special Republican Guard]] Brigades, 10 commando, and two Special Forces Brigades.<ref name=IISS97>IISS Military Balance 1997-98</ref> It was estimated to number 350,000 personnel, including 100,000 recently recalled reservists.<ref name=IISS97 />\n\n===Invasion of 2003===\n\nIn the days leading up to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and the following [[Iraq War]], the army consisted of 375,000 troops, organized into five [[corps]]. In all, there were 11 [[infantry]] [[division (military)|divisions]], 3 [[mechanized infantry|mechanized]] divisions, and 3 [[division (military)#Armored divisions|armored divisions]].  The Republican Guard consisted of between 50,000 and 60,000 troops (although some sources indicate a strength of up to 80,000).\n\nIn January 2003, before the start of the invasion of Iraq in March 2003, the force was primarily located in eastern [[Iraq]]. The five corps were organised as follows:\n* [[1st Corps (Iraq)|1st Corps]], near [[Kirkuk]] consisted of the 5th Mechanized Division, 2nd Infantry Division, 8th Infantry Division and the 38th Infantry Division.\n* [[2nd Corps (Iraq)|2nd Corps]], near [[Diyala Governorate|Diyala]], had the 3rd Armored Division, 15th Infantry Division, and 34th Infantry Division.<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2003/iraq/forces/iraq/army/</ref>\n* [[3rd Corps (Iraq)|3rd Corps]], near [[An Nasiriyah]], had the 6th Armored Division, the 51st Mechanized Division, and the 11th Infantry Division.<ref name=MalMap />\n* [[4th Corps (Iraq)|4th Corps]], near [[Amarah]], included the [[10th Armored Division (Iraq)|10th Armored Division]], 14th Infantry Division and 18th Infantry Division.<ref name=MalMap>Malovany, \"Wars of Modern Babylon,\" pp. 662-663.</ref>\n* 5th Corps, near [[Mosul]], had the [[1st Mechanised Division (Iraq)|1st Mechanised Division]], and the [[4th Infantry Division (Iraq)|4th]], 7th, and 16th Infantry Divisions.\n* Western Desert Force, consisting of an [[Mechanized infantry|armored infantry]] division and other units in western Iraq.\n\nMalovany's description of deployments generally follows this pattern, A special headquarters was established on the eve of the war called the \"Great Day\" to command forces defending the Anbar district in west Iraq and the axes leading from it towards Baghdad.<ref name=MalMap />\n\nDuring the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] the Iraqi Army was defeated in a number of battles, including by [[Task Force Viking]] in the north, and the [[Battle of Nasiriyah]] and the [[Battle of Baghdad (2003)|Battle of Baghdad]]. The Iraqi Army was disbanded by [[Coalition Provisional Authority Order Number 2]] issued by U.S. Administrator of Iraq [[Paul Bremer]] on May 23, 2003 after its decisive defeat.<ref name=\"ISMFD\">Iraqi Security and Military Force Developments: A Chronology, 2, 4, 6, 7 [http://www.csis.org/media/csis/pubs/060330_securityforceschronology.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145310/http://www.csis.org/media/csis/pubs/060330_securityforceschronology.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }}</ref> Bremer said that it was not feasible to reconstitute the armed forces.  His justifications for the disbandment included postwar looting, which had destroyed all the bases; that the largely Shiite draftees of the army would not respond to a recall plea from their former commanders, who were primarily Sunnis, and that recalling the army would be a political disaster because to the vast majority of Iraqis it was a symbol of the old Baathist-led Sunni ascendancy...\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/06/opinion/06bremer.html?ex=1346817600&en=278710834dcd1971&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | work=The New York Times | title=How I Didn't Dismantle Iraq's Army | date=2007-09-06 | accessdate=2010-05-04 | first=L. Paul | last=Bremer III | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423154005/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/06/opinion/06bremer.html?ex=1346817600&en=278710834dcd1971&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | archive-date=2009-04-23 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Formations of the army, 1922\u20132003==\n\n===Corps===\n* [[1st Corps (Iraq)|1st Corps]] \u2013 established before Iran-Iraq War.\n* [[2nd Corps (Iraq)|2nd Corps]] \u2013 reorganised as an armoured corps for the 1991 [[Gulf War]], comprising the 17th Armoured Division and the 51st Mechanised Division\n* [[3rd Corps (Iraq)|3rd Corps]] \u2013 established before Iran-Iraq War. In 1978 reported to be headquartered at [[Nasariyah]] and to consist of 1st and 5th Mechanised Divisions and [[9th Armoured Division (Iraq)|9th Armoured Division]]. In 2003, Nasiriyah was the headquarters of the Iraqi Army's 3rd Corps, composed of the 11th ID, 51st Mech ID, and [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Armored Division]]\u2014all at around 50 percent strength. The 51st operated south covering the oilfields, and the 6th was north near [[Al Amarah]], which left three brigade-sized elements of the 11th ID to guard the An Nasiriyah area.<ref name=rohr>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mca-marines.org/GAZETTE/06rohr.asp |title=Fighting Through the Fog of War |publisher=Marine Corps Gazette |first=Karl |last=Rohr |accessdate=29 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201131311/http://www.mca-marines.org/Gazette/06rohr.asp |archivedate=December 1, 2008}}</ref>\n* 4th Corps \u2013 established 22 October 1981 to take over the northern sector of [[Khuzestan Province]], including Basitin, Shush, and Dezful sectors. Maj Gen Hisham Sahab al-Fakhri, previously 10th Armoured Division commander, was appointed as the corps commander. 1st Mechanised, 10th Armoured, and 14th Infantry Division were allocated to the corps, leaving 3rd Corps with 3rd and 9th Armoured, 5th Mechanised, and 11th Infantry Divisions.<ref>Malovany 168</ref>\n* 5th Corps\n* 6th Corps \u2013 Malovany 2017 writes that on 25 March 1985, an army meeting chaired by Saddam in Baghdad decided to transform the East Tigris Headquarters into a regular corps, the 6th Corps. It was to be reinforced with four additional divisions; as the 35th Division had been transferred to the 4th Corps, and the 32nd Division was with the East Tigris HQ, the new line-up would consist of the 32nd Division as before; the 12th Armoured Division and [[2nd Infantry Division (Iraq)|2nd Infantry Division]] transferred both from the 2nd Corps; the [[4th Infantry Division (Iraq)|4th Infantry Division]], and the 25th Infantry Division from the 4th Corps.<ref>Malovany 2017, 277.</ref> Malovany adds on the same page that during 1986 two more divisions joined the 6th Corps, an infantry division (\"apparently the 50th\") and the \"Marshes\" Division.\n* 7th Corps\n* Jihad Forces ([[Persian Gulf War]] of 1991)\n\n===Infantry and mechanised divisions===\n* [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st Division]], active from at least 1941. 1st Mechanised Division in [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]] and [[Iraq War]]. Reformed after 2003.\n* [[2nd Division (Iraq)|2nd Division]], active from at least 1941\n* [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Division]], active from at least 1941. Served in Iran\u2013Iraq War\n* [[4th Division (Iraq)|4th Division]], active from at least 1941. As 4th Mountain Infantry Division, served in Iran\u2013Iraq War.\n* [[5th Division (Iraq)|5th Division]], activated 1959. Served in Iran\u2013Iraq War. As 5th Mechanised Division, fought in [[Battle of Khafji]].\n* [[7th Division (Iraq)|7th Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War\n* [[8th Division (Iraq)|8th Division]]. As 8th Mountain Infantry Division, served in Iran\u2013Iraq War.\n* [[11th Division (Iraq)|11th Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]\n* [[14th Division (Iraq)|14th Division]]\n* [[15th Infantry Division (Iraq)|15th Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War ([[Operation Beit-ol-Moqaddas]])\n* 16th, 18th, 19th, 20th, 21st, 22nd, 23rd, 24th, 25th Divisions,\n* 26th, 27th,<ref>See Gulf War Air Power Survey, Vol. I, pg 68/97.</ref> 28th, 28th, 30th, 31st, 33rd, 34th, 36th, 37th, 38th Divisions\n* 39th, 42nd, 44th, 45th, 46th, 47th, 48th, 49th, 50th,\n* 51st Mechanised Division (surrendered during Iraqi Freedom 22 March 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/03/21/sprj.irq.division.surrender/index.html|title=CNN.com - Iraqi army division gives up fight - Mar. 22, 2003|website=edition.cnn.com|access-date=2018-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710075208/http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/03/21/sprj.irq.division.surrender/index.html|archive-date=2016-07-10|url-status=live}}</ref>)\n* 53rd, 54th, 56th Divisions\n* Eisenstadt reported 'about eight infantry divisions remain unaccounted for' as of March 1993.<ref name=\"Michael Eisenstadt 1993, p.124\" />\n\n===Armoured divisions up to 2003===\n* [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Armoured Division]], active by 1967, served in [[Yom Kippur War]], [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]\n* [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Armoured Division]], served in Yom Kippur War, Iran\u2013Iraq War\n* [[9th Armoured Division (Iraq)]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, disbanded after First Battle of Basrah/[[Operation Ramadan]], July 1982 (Pollack p.&nbsp;205). Reformed after 2003.\n* [[10th Division (Iraq)|10th Armoured Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, in [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]] with Jihad Forces (corps)\n* [[12th Division (Iraq)|12th Armoured Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, Persian Gulf War with Jihad Forces (corps)\n* [[17th Division (Iraq)|17th Armoured Division]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/17ad.htm|title=17th Armored Division|first=John|last=Pike|website=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=2010-08-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109182348/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/17ad.htm|archive-date=2009-01-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 52nd Armoured Division\n\n===Brigades===\nThe 65th Special Forces Brigade, 66th Special Forces Brigade, 68th Special Forces Brigade, and 440th Marine Brigade were active during the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]. (Eisenstadt)\n\n==Reform of the army==\n[[File:Iraqi T-72 tanks and an M113 APC from the Iraqi Army 9th Mechanized Division pass through a highway checkpoint in Mushahada, Iraq.jpg|thumb|right|Iraqi Asad Babil tanks and an M113 APC from the Iraqi Army 9th Mechanized Division pass through a highway checkpoint in Mushahada, Iraq.]]\nBased on Bush administration expectations that coalition forces would be welcomed as liberators after the overthrow of the Hussein regime,<ref>Christopher Spearin, 'A Justified Heaping of the Blame?,' in Stoker (ed). Military Advising and Assistance, Routledge, 2008, p.229</ref> prewar planners had only been expecting little if any resistance from the Iraqi people. Thus the new army was initially focused on external defence operations. The new Army was originally intended to comprise 27 battalions in three divisions numbering 40,000 soldiers in three years time. [[Vinnell Corporation]] was engaged to train the first nine battalions.<ref>Charles Tiefer, \"The Iraq Debacle: The Rise and Fall of Procurement-Aided Unilateralism as a Paradigm of Foreign War,\" University of Pennsylvania Journal of Int'l Law 29 (2007)</ref>\n\nThe [[Coalition Military Assistance Training Team]] (CMATT), headed by Major General [[Paul Eaton]], was the organization set up by the [[Department of Defense (United States)|Department of Defense]] with the responsibility of training and development of the new army. On August 2, 2003, the first battalion of new Iraqi Army recruits started a nine-week training course at a training base in [[Qaraqosh]]. They graduated on October 4, 2003.<ref name=\"CPA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpa-iraq.org/pressreleases/20031007_Oct-04-NIAGrad.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040701212721/http://www.cpa-iraq.org/pressreleases/20031007_Oct-04-NIAGrad.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-07-01|access-date=July 1, 2004|date=October 2003|title=CPA-IRAQ.org: Homepage of The New Iraq - Information about the Iraqi Dinar|website=www.cpa-iraq.org}}</ref>\n\nIn the interim, the new army had been formally established by [[Coalition Provisional Authority Order 22]] of August 7, 2003.\n\nIn April 2004, several Iraqi battalions refused to fight as part of the force engaged in the [[First Battle of Fallujah]].<ref name=\"West2011\">{{cite book|author=Bing West|title=No True Glory: A Frontline Account of the Battle for Fallujah|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SWaSHGkYEBoC|date=7 December 2011|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-80834-9|page=118|access-date=10 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012122337/https://books.google.com/books?id=SWaSHGkYEBoC|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Fifth Battalion was among the new Iraqi units that fought in Fallujah.<ref>* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9xF0DQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Zacchea+Kemp+The+Ragged+Edge&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7uu6YkrDVAhUFHJQKHXH3DGwQ6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q=Zacchea%20Kemp%20The%20Ragged%20Edge&f=false|title=Ragged Edge: A US Marine's Account of Leading the Iraqi Army Fifth Battalion|last=Zacchea|first=Michael|last2=Kemp|first2=Ted|date=2017-04-01|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781613738443|language=en|access-date=2017-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012122810/https://books.google.com/books?id=9xF0DQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Zacchea+Kemp+The+Ragged+Edge&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7uu6YkrDVAhUFHJQKHXH3DGwQ6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q=Zacchea%20Kemp%20The%20Ragged%20Edge&f=false|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2004, the CMATT was dissolved, and passed on its responsibilities to the [[Multi-National Security Transition Command \u2013 Iraq]] (MNSTC-I) (initially headed by Lt. Gen. [[David Petraeus]]) with the new focus on providing security for the Iraqi people from the emerging threat posed by the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/congress/2005_hr/050314-sepp.pdf |title=Prepared Statement before the House Subcommittee on National Security, Emerging Threats, and International Relations regarding the training of Iraqi Security Forces |author=[[Kalev Sepp]] |date=2005-03-14 |accessdate=2008-10-07 |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20050523220734/http://reform.house.gov/UploadedFiles/Sepp%20Testimony.pdf |archivedate=May 23, 2005 |format=PDF |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhile the regular army was being formed, U.S. commanders around the country needed additional troops more quickly, and thus the [[Iraqi Civil Defense Corps]] (which became the [[National Guard (Iraq)|Iraqi National Guard]] by July 2004)<ref name=\"Al-MarashiSalama2008\">{{cite book|author1=Ibrahim Al-Marashi|author2=Sammy Salama|title=Iraq's Armed Forces: An Analytical History|url=https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma|url-access=registration|date=7 April 2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-14564-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma/page/212 212]|access-date=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> was formed. Coalition commanders formed these militia-type units separately in each area; only later were they gradually brought together as one force. There were several instances where they have refused to take military action against fellow Iraqis, such as in [[Fallujah]], deserted, or allegedly aided the resistance. It is alleged that most guardsmen were drawn from the [[Shia]] majority in Southern Iraq or the [[Kurd]]ish majority in northern Iraq, rather than from the [[Sunni]] area which they were ordered to attack. In September 2004, a senior member of the National Guard, General Talib al-Lahibi was arrested on suspicion of having links with insurgent groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/3691540.stm|title=US arrests senior Iraqi commander|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331004205/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/3691540.stm|archive-date=31 March 2007|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In December 2004, it was announced that the Iraqi National Guard would be dissolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/4133039.stm|title=Iraq to dissolve National Guard|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228051413/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/4133039.stm|archive-date=28 February 2007|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At this time its strength was officially over 40,000 men. Its units became part of the army. The absorption of the ING by the regular army appears to have taken place on January 6, 2005, Iraqi Army Day.<ref>Cordesman and Baetjer, 2006, p.147-148. On the ING, see Neil Barnett, 'Iraq's turbulent transition,' [[Jane's Defence Weekly]], 8 September 2004, p.23</ref>\n\nOn August 14, 2004, the [[NATO Training Mission - Iraq]] was established to assist the Iraqi military, including the army. On September 20 the provisional Fallujah Brigade dissolved after being sent in to secure the city. The Fallujah Brigade experiment of using former insurgents to secure a city was not repeated.\n\nArmy training was transferred from [[Vinnell Corporation]] to the [[United States armed forces]] supported by U.S. allies, and is now done by three Iraqi training battalions. Training was impeded by domestic instability, infiltration by insurgents, and high desertion rates.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}} In June 2005, the partnership between Coalition forces and Iraqi forces has increased due to the growing number of battalions in the Iraqi army, which then stood around 115. Out of this number, it was deemed that 80 of them were able to carry out operations in the field with Coalition support limited to logistics and strategic planning, whilst another 20-30 battalions still needed major Coalition support to carry out their operations. As of October 5, 2005 the Iraqi Army had 90 battalions trained well enough to be \"deployed independently\", i.e. without the help of others such as the United States.<ref>The Long War Journal, [http://billroggio.com/archives/2005/10/training_the_ir_1.php Training the Iraqi Army - Revisited, Again] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070408181617/http://billroggio.com/archives/2005/10/training_the_ir_1.php |date=2007-04-08 }}, 2005</ref>\n\n[[File:Iraqi army 03 2011.jpg|thumb|Iraqi [[commandos]] training under the supervision of soldiers of the US [[82nd Airborne]].]]\nOn May 3, 2006 a significant command-and-control development took place. The Iraqi Army command and control center opened in a ceremony at the [[Iraqi Ground Forces Command]] (IFGC) headquarters at [[Camp Victory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Daily/May/060504.htm|title=Iraqi command and control center opens doors amidst turnover of new territory|date=2006-05-04|publisher=[[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708233659/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Daily/May/060504.htm|archivedate=2006-07-08}}</ref> The IGFC was established to exercise command and control of assigned Iraqi Army forces and, upon assuming Operational Control, to plan and direct operations to defeat the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]]. At the time, the IFGC was commanded by Lt. Gen. Abdul-Qadar. In 2006 the ten planned divisions began to be certified and assume battlespace responsibility: the 6th and 8th before June 26, 2006, the 9th on June 26, 2006, the 5th on July 3, 2006, the 4th on August 8, 2006, and the 2nd on December 21, 2006. After divisions were certified, they began to be transferred from U.S. operational control to Iraqi control of the IGFC. The 8th Division was transferred on September 7, 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/10359|title=US hands over control of Iraq military|date=7 September 2006|website=Iraq Updates|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116040104/http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/10359|archive-date=16 January 2009|url-status=dead|access-date=3 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2006/09/200849134437544335.html|title=US hands over control of Iraq military|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104192311/https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2006/09/200849134437544335.html|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> and the 3rd Division on December 1, 2006. Another unspecified division also was transferred to IGFC control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=2270|title=Iraqis to Command Four Northern Divisions by February, U.S. General Says|publisher=U.S. Department of defense|date=December 1, 2006|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130123733/http://www.defenselink.mil/news/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=2270|archive-date=30 November 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also transferred to the Iraqi [[chain of command]] were smaller logistics units: on November 1, 2006, the 5th Motor Transport Regiment (MTR) was the fifth of nine MTRs to be transferred to the Iraqi Army divisions. 2007 plans included, MNF-I said, great efforts to make the Iraqi Army able to sustain itself logistically.<ref>MTRs transferred in order of event: 8th, 4th, 6th, 5th and 1st (2 Nov). [http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7392&Itemid=109 IA 5th MTR driving toward success - Daily article on www.mnf-iraq.com, 20 November 2006.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929105112/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7392&Itemid=109 |date=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAs of June 26, 2006, three Iraqi divisions, 18 brigades and 69 battalions were in control of battlespace (including two police commando battalions).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/PentagonPresser/060623-casey-rumsfeld.htm|title=Pentagon Press Briefing June 23, 2006, with Secretary Donald Rumsfeld and Gen. George Casey|publisher=MNF-I|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112041117/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/PentagonPresser/060623-casey-rumsfeld.htm|archive-date=12 January 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\n[[File:080216 3-14 graduation.jpg|thumb|Members of Iraqi Army 3rd Brigade, [[14th Division (Iraq)|14th Division]] participate in a parade for Iraqi and Coalition military members attending the graduation ceremony, February 13.]]\n\nOn March 25, 2008, the Iraqi Army launched its first solely planned and executed high-profile division-level operation, [[Battle of Basra (2008)|Operation Charge of the Knights]] in Basra. They received [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]] support only in air support, logistics and via embedded advisors. Also, a British infantry brigade, part of [[Multi-National Division (South-East) (Iraq)|Multi-National Division South-East]], and stationed in Basra, were ready in a tactical overwatch role. Their participation was limited to the provision of embedded training teams.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nIn April\u2013June 2008, two brigades of the Iraqi Army 11th Division, supported by US forces, moved into the southern third of [[Sadr City]]. They were tasked to stop rocket and mortar attacks on US bases and the [[Green Zone]]. Following the [[Siege of Sadr City]]\u2014a month of fighting\u2014the [[Mahdi Army]] agreed to let Iraqi forces into the remaining portion of the city. On May 20, troops from the Iraqi Army 3rd Brigade of the [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st (Iraqi Reaction Force) Division]] and a brigade from the 9th Division moved into the northern districts of Sadr City and began clearing operations.\n\nIn May,  Iraqi army forces launched [[Operation Lion's Roar]] (later renamed to Operation Mother of Two Springs) in Mosul and surrounding areas of Nineveh Governorate. Iraq became one of the top purchasers of U.S. military equipment with the Iraqi army trading its [[AK-47]] assault rifles for the more accurate U.S. [[M16 rifle|M-16]] and [[M4 Carbine|M-4]] rifles, among other equipment.<ref>Ceerwan Aziz, [https://www.usatoday.com/news/military/2008-05-21-iraqarms_N.htm \"Iraqi forces load up on U.S. arms,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314035113/http://www.usatoday.com/news/military/2008-05-21-iraqarms_N.htm |date=2012-03-14}} ''USA Today'' (5/22/2008). Retrieved 11 October 2014</ref>\n\nIn June 2008 the army moved troops to the southern [[Maysan Governorate]]. Following a four-day amnesty for insurgents to turn over weapons, the Iraqi Army moved into the provincial capital Amarah.\n\n===2012===\nEach of the joint and multi-agency operational commands also include the [[Department of Border Enforcement]] (DBE), Federal Police, Emergency Police, Oil Police, FPS, etc. in their command as well as Iraqi Army.\n\nAs of the Fall of 2012, the Iraqi Army was organized as follows:\n* National Operations Center \u2013 [[Baghdad]]\n** Baghdad Operational Command \u2013 Baghdad<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage7-IGFC-B.pdf|title=Microsoft Word \u2013 OOBpage7-IGFC-B.rtf|access-date=2008-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145308/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage7-IGFC-B.pdf|archive-date=2008-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 Lt. Gen. [[Abud Qanbar]]\n*** Karkh Area Command (KAC) \u2013 Western Baghdad. Responsible for the Kadhimiyah, Karkh, Mansour, Bayaa, and Doura Security Districts.\n*** Rusafa Area Command (RAC) \u2013 Eastern Baghdad. Responsible for the Adhamiyah, Rusafa, Sadr City, New Baghdad, and Karadah Security Districts.\n*** [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Motorised Division]] \u2013 Western Baghdad.\n*** [[9th Division (Iraq)|9th Armored Division]] \u2013 Taji \u2013 Division certified and assumes responsibility of the battle space of the northern [[Baghdad Governorate]] on June 26, 2006.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Publications/TWII/060626.pdf This Week in Iraq \u2013 MNF-I Newsletter] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060711234430/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Publications/TWII/060626.pdf |date=2006-07-11}}, June 26, 2006</ref>\n*** [[11th Division (Iraq)|11th Infantry Division]] \u2013 East Baghdad (probably planned to become a mechanized division).\n*** [[17th Division (Iraq)|17th Commando Division]] \u2013 HQ [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmadiyah]] The 17th Division commander has been reported as Staff Maj. Gen. Ali Jassam Mohammad.\n*** 23rd Commando Brigade\n*** 25th Commando Brigade \u2013 'Baghdad Eagles' \u2013 former 4th Bde, 6th Div. Has received commando training by U.S. [[Special Forces]] and air assault training.\n*** 55th Commando Brigade\n** Niniweh Operational Command<ref>Long War Journal, [http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage5-IGFC-M.pdf Microsoft Word \u2013 OOBpage5-IGFC-M.rtf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145306/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage5-IGFC-M.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }}</ref> \u2013 Mosul\n*** [[2nd Division (Iraq)|2nd Division]] \u2013 [[Mosul]] destroyed by ISIS in 2014\n*** [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Motorised Division]] \u2013 [[Al-Kasik]] destroyed by ISIS in 2014\n*** [[15th Infantry Division (Iraq)|15th Division]] Formed in 2015\n*** 16th Division\n** Diyala Operational Command \u2013 Sulamaniyah, Diyala, Kirkuk, Salahadin\n*** [[4th Division (Iraq)|4th Motorised Division]] \u2013 Tikrit \u2013 Division certified on August 8, 2006.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1894&Itemid=18 Daily story on MNF-I Webpage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913030540/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1894&Itemid=18 |date=2007-09-13}}, August 9, 2006</ref>\n*** [[5th Division (Iraq)|5th Infantry Division]] (Iron) \u2013 [[Diyala Governorate]] \u2013 Division certified on July 3, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mnstci.iraq.centcom.mil/docs/advisor/currentissue.pdf |title=The Advisor, MNSTC-I Newsletter, July 8, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112011941/http://www.mnstci.iraq.centcom.mil/docs/advisor/currentissue.pdf |archivedate=2006-11-12|format=PDF}}</ref>\n*** [[12th Division (Iraq)|12th Motorized Division]] \u2013 Tikrit \u2013 split off from 4 Div in mid-2008.\n** Basrah Operational Command \u2013 Basrah\n*** [[8th Division (Iraq)|8th Commando Division]] \u2013 HQ [[Diwaniyah]]\n*** [[10th Division (Iraq)|10th Commando Division]] \u2013 [[An Nasiriyah]]\n*** [[14th Division (Iraq)|14th Division]] \u2013 Basrah<ref>[http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage9-IAJoint%20forming.pdf Page 9: IGFC Basrah Sector] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145307/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage9-IAJoint%20forming.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }} - Long War Journal</ref> \u2013 division commander Maj. Gen. Abdul Aziz Noor Swady al Dalmy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mil/-news/2010/01/25/33467-iraqi-bedouins-seek-role-in-secure-future/|title=Iraqi Bedouins seek role in secure future|date=25 January 2010|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n** Anbar Operational Command \u2013 Ramadi\n*** [[File:\u0634\u0639\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0644 \u062a\u062f\u062e\u0644 \u0633\u0631\u064a\u0639 copy.jpg|25px]] [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st Infantry Division]] \u2013 Fallujah destroyed by ISIS in 2014\n*** [[7th Division (Iraq)|7th Infantry Division]] \u2013 Ramadi, West [[Al Anbar]] Province \u2013 transferred to Iraqi Ground Forces Command on November 1, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15012&Itemid=128|title=\"7th Iraqi Army Division now Controlled by Iraqi Government\", MNF-I Press Release November 03 2007|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132016===\nIn summer 2014, large elements of the Iraqi army were routed by a much smaller and less well-equipped force from the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].\n\nBudget problems continued to hinder the manning of combat support and combat service support units. The lack of soldiers entering boot camp is forcing Iraqi leaders at all levels to face the dual challenge of manning and training enabler units out of existing manpower. In the 2015 Pentagon budget, a further $1.3 billion has been requested to provide weapons for the Iraqi Army.<ref name=\"The New York Times\" /> However, the New York Times reported that \"some of the weaponry recently supplied by the army has already ended up on the black market and in the hands of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] fighters\". The same November 2014 article contended that corruption is endemic in the Iraqi Army. It quoted Col. Shaaban al-Obeidi of the internal security forces, who told the paper's David D Kirkpatrick: \"Corruption is everywhere.\" The article claimed that one Iraqi general is known as \"chicken guy\" because of his reputation for selling the soldiers' poultry provisions.<ref name=\"The New York Times\" />\n\nDivisions are forming engineer, logistics, mortar, and other units by identifying over-strength units, such as the Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR) battalions and other headquarters elements, and then transferring them as needed.\n\nProblems include infiltration and an insufficient US advisory effort. The new army aimed to exclude recruits that are former regime security and intelligence organizations members, personnel of the [[Special Republican Guard]], top-level Ba'ath Party members, and Ba'ath Party security and militia organizations.<ref name=\"New Iraqi Army NIA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/nia.htm|title=New Iraqi Army (NIA)|author=John Pike|accessdate=11 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006075831/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/nia.htm|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However the army is widely known to have been infiltrated by a multitude of groups ranging from local militias to foreign insurgents. This has led to highly publicized deaths and compromised operations.\n\nThe [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]] are a [[Ministry of Defence (Iraq)]] funded component that reports directly to the [[Prime Minister of Iraq]].<ref name=\"New Iraqi Army NIA\" />\nIn late June 2014, after the large-scale [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] offensive in the north of Iraq, it was reported that ISIL \"\"took the weapons stores of the 2nd and 3rd [Iraqi army] divisions in Mosul, the [[4th Division (Iraq)|4th division]] in Salah al Din, the [[12th Division (Iraq)|12th division]] in the areas near Kirkuk, and another division in Diyala (the [[5th Division (Iraq)|5th Division]]),\" said Jabbar Yawar, secretary-general of the Kurkish Ministry of Peshmerga Affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-iraq-isis-arms-20140629-story.html|title=ISIS weapons windfall may alter balance in Iraq, Syria conflicts|first=Raja|last=Abdulrahim|date=29 June 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065329/http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-iraq-isis-arms-20140629-story.html|archive-date=13 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nReuters reported that the [[5th Division (Iraq)]], located in [[Diyala Governorate]], was by October 2014 reporting to informal \"militias' chain of command,\" not to the Iraqi Army, according to several U.S. and coalition military officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/iraq-abadi/|title=Power failure in Iraq as militias outgun state|first=Ned|last=Parker|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2017-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024225300/http://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/iraq-abadi/|archive-date=2017-10-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA much later report from Small Wars Journal said that in \"..2013 and 2014 the 7th Division of the Iraqi Army, 99% Sunni, fought IS virtually alone, until it was almost completely destroyed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/the-iraqi-military-the-us-led-coalition-and-the-mosul-operation-the-risk-of-snatching-defea|title=The Iraqi Military, The US-led Coalition and the Mosul Operation: The Risk of Snatching Defeat from the Jaws of Victory \u2013 Small Wars Journal|website=smallwarsjournal.com|access-date=2017-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013124113/http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/the-iraqi-military-the-us-led-coalition-and-the-mosul-operation-the-risk-of-snatching-defea|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe October 2014 Reuters report quoted Lieutenant General [[John Michael Bednarek|Mick Bednarek]], Chief of the [[Office of Security Cooperation]], in Iraq from 2013 until July 2014, as estimating that \"the army has only five functioning divisions ... whose fighting readiness ranges between 60 and 65 percent.\"\n\nMichael Knights wrote in 2016 that the rebuilding from the mid-2014 disaster had been steady but \"very slow\". \"By January 2015 a fair number of brigades had been salvaged and a couple of new brigades were built but the overall frontline combat strength of the ISF was halved due to attrition in the manning of each brigade. [U]nits were weaker and many were too demoralized or lightly equipped to do more than hold in place. A year later, by January 2016, significant progress has been made in terms of available forces albeit largely by shuffling around personnel and raising around a dozen new and very small 1,000-strong brigades.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/The-future.pdf|title=The Future of Iraq's Armed Forces|last=Knights|first=Michael|publisher=Al-Bayan Center for Planning and Studies|year=March 2016|publication-place=Baghdad|pages=22|access-date=2017-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921164909/https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/The-future.pdf|archive-date=2017-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref> The new 15th and 16th Divisions have been identified, which appear to comprise some of the new brigades that Knights mentions, including the 71st, 72nd, 73rd, 75th, and 76th.\n\nThe Institute for the Study of War said in their 29 December 2014 situation report that \"..The [[19th Division (Iraq)|19th Division]] is a new military formation intended to include members from the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, and 12th IA divisions that melted away during the rapid advance of ISIS in June of 2014. This formation will almost certainly include volunteer fighters, most likely displaced persons from Mosul, who reside in refugee camps. The.. sectarian composition of the unit will be important to watch. The formation of the division was initially proposed by Defense Minister [[Khaled al-Obaidi]] on November 4, 2014 during a visit to Iraqi Kurdistan. During that visit he requested assistance from the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]] [with] basing the new division in Iraqi Kurdistan and giving the force responsibility for clearing Mosul.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/2015-1-1-2%20Situation%20Report.pdf|title=Iraq Situation Report: January 1-2, 2015|publisher=Institute for the Study of War|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230616/http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/2015-1-1-2%20Situation%20Report.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe Iraqi Army began the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]] with a force of four divisions. A fifth was formed in 1959. By the outbreak of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]], the force had grown to nine divisions. By 1990, with wartime expansion, the force had grown greatly to at least 56 divisions, making the Iraqi army the fourth largest army in the world and one of the strongest in the Middle East. After the defeat in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]] in 1991, force size dropped to around 23 divisions, as well as [[Iraqi Republican Guard|Republican Guard]] formations. The new army formed after 2003 was initially planned to be three divisions strong, but was then raised to ten divisions, and the force is now expected to grow to 20 divisions.\n\nThe U.S. [[House Armed Services Committee]] commented in 2007 that \"It is important to note that in the initial fielding plan, five army divisions would be tied to the regions from where they were recruited and the other five would be deployable throughout Iraq. This was partially due to the legacy of some army divisions being formed from the National Guard units and has caused some complications in terms of making these forces available for operations in all areas of Iraq, and the military becoming a truly national, non-sectarian force.\"<ref>[[House Armed Services Committee]], {{cite web|url=http://armedservices.house.gov/pdfs/OI_ISFreport062707/OI_Report_FINAL.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070627175546/http://armedservices.house.gov/pdfs/OI_ISFreport062707/OI_Report_FINAL.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 June 2007|title=THE CONTINUING CHALLENGE OF BUILDING THE IRAQI SECURITY FORCES (note 53, page 120)|format=PDF|date=27 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Department of Defense]] ''Measuring Safety and Security in Iraq'' report of August 2006, plans at that time called for the Iraqi Army to be built up to an approximately 300,000-person force. This was based around an Army with 10 infantry divisions and 6 mechanised infantry division consisting of 36 brigades and 113 battalions (91 infantry, 12 special forces, 24 mechanised infantry, 60 armored battalions, 1 security). Nine Motorized Transportation Regiments, 5 logistics battalions, 2 support battalions, 5 Regional Support Units (RSUs), and 91 Garrison Support Units (GSUs) are intended to provide logistics and support for each division, with Taji National Depot providing  depot-level maintenance and resupply. Each battalion, brigade, and division headquarters will be supported by a Headquarters and Service Company (HSC) providing logistical and maintenance support to its parent organisation. The army will also include 17 SIBs and a Special Operations Forces Brigade consisting of two special operational battalions.<ref name=\"MSSIAug06\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|title=United States Department of Defense|website=www.defenselink.mil|access-date=2007-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911200618/http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|archive-date=2007-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Iraqi tanks during the parade.jpg|thumb|left|Iraqi T-72s pass in review in Baghdad, June 30, 2009.]]\nThe Iraqi Army consists of nine regional joint commands. The Joint Operational Commands fall under the command of the National Operations Center.  The [[Iraqi Ground Forces Command]] does not directly command the army's divisions.\n\nAs of July 2009, the Iraqi Army had 14 divisions (1st-12th, 14th, and 17th, the designation 13 not being used), containing 56 brigades or 185 combat battalions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} The 6th Division and the 17th Division are still missing their fourth manoeuvre brigades. By April 2010, the combat battalion total had risen to 197 combat battalions.  Each division has four line brigades, an engineering regiment, and a support regiment.\n\nThree of the 56 brigades are not [[Iraqi Ground Forces Command]] combatant brigades and are not assigned to a division.  They are the [[Baghdad Brigade]] formed in the fall of 2008, the [[1st Presidential Brigade]] formed in January 2008, and the [[2nd Presidential Brigade]] formed in the spring of 2009.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n== Rank insignia ==\n{{main|Military ranks of Iraq}}\n\n==Training==\n[[File:Iraqi soldier with AKM.jpg|thumb|left|Iraqi soldiers perform a live-fire exercise using Bulgarian AR-M1 rifles.]]\n[[File:Female iraqi soldier with a Kalashnikov.JPEG|thumb|left|A [[Women in the military|female Iraqi soldier]] during live weapons training at the Jordanian Royal Military Academy.]]\n[[File:Iraqi T-72 tank fires.JPG|thumb|left|An Iraqi Army T-72 tank performs a live-fire training exercise at the [[Besmaya Range Complex|Besmaya Gunnery Range]], in Besmaya, Baghdad, 28 October 2008.]]\n\nThere are three levels of troop capability in the new army: one, two, and three. Level three refers to troops that have just completed basic training, level two refers to troops that are able to work with soldiers, and level one refers to troops that can work by themselves.\n\nMembers of [[NATO Training Mission \u2013 Iraq]] (NTM-I) opened a Joint Staff College in [[ar Rustamiyah]] in Baghdad on September 27, 2005 with 300 trainers. Training at bases in Norway, Italy, Jordan, Germany, and Egypt has also taken place and 16 NATO countries have allocated forces to the training effort.<ref>Jeremy M. Sharp and Christopher M. Blanchard - [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/mideast/RL32105.pdf Post-War Iraq:Foreign Contributions to Training, Peacekeeping, and Reconstruction] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924132513/http://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/mideast/RL32105.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }} - Congressional Research Service</ref>\n\nThe [[Multi-National Force Iraq]] has also conducted a variety of training programs for both enlisted soldiers and officers including training as [[medic]]s, [[engineer]]s, [[quartermaster]]s, and [[military police]].  Beyond the various courses and programs being held in-country, both American [[staff college]]s and [[military academy|military academies]] have begun taking Iraqi applicants, with Iraqi cadets being enrolled at both the [[United States Military Academy]] and the [[United States Air Force Academy|US Air Force Academy]].<ref>DJ Elliott and CJ Radin - [http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage3-JFC.pdf Iraqi Security Forces Order of Battle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145309/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage3-JFC.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }} - Long War Journal</ref>\n\n===Recruits and enlisted soldiers===\nIraqi Army recruits undergo a standard eight-week <ref name=\"CRS 2007-04-27\">Iraq - Post-Saddam Governance and Security, ''CRS Report for Congress'', p.41</ref> basic training course that includes basic soldiering skills, weapons marksmanship and individual tactics.  Former soldiers are eligible for an abbreviated three-week \"Direct Recruit Replacement Training\" course designed to replace regular basic training to be followed by more training once they have been assigned to a unit.\n\nSoldiers later go on to enroll in more specific advanced courses targeted for their respective fields.  This could involve going to the Military Intelligence School, the Signal School, the Bomb Disposal School, the Combat Arms Branch School, the Engineer School, and the Military Police School.\n\n===Officers===\nThe Iraqi Armed Service and Supply Institute located in [[Taji]] plays a significant role in training aspiring Iraqi [[non-commissioned officer]]s and [[commissioned officers]].  The training is based on a [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] model, chosen in part due to its shorter graduation time compared to [[United States Military Academy|West Point]]. Much of the Iraqi officer training programme is copied directly from the Sandhurst course.\n\nCMATT's main recruiting stations are located in [[Baghdad]], [[Basra]] and [[Mosul]]. The most desired recruits are individuals who have prior military service or are skilled in specific professions such as first aid, heavy equipment operation, food service and truck driving. A recruitment target of approximately one thousand soldiers is desired to eventually form a 757-man battalion.  Soldier fallout usually occurs due to voluntary withdrawal or failure to meet training standards.\n\nDue to the current demand for these battalions to become active as soon as possible, the first four battalions' officers, non-commissioned officers, and enlisted soldiers are being trained simultaneously (in separate groups). Notable differences in training between CAATT and former training under [[Saddam Hussein|Saddam]]'s regime include schooling in human rights, the laws of land warfare, and tolerance in a multi-ethnic team.\n\nBased on the philosophy used by the U.S. military to boost its own size in response to World War II \u2014 that an army can be built faster by focusing on the training on its leadership rather than enlisted soldiers \u2014 CMATT has pursued a similar strategy of focusing recruitment and training on commissioned and non-commissioned officers for the remaining 23 Iraqi battalions. Upon successful completion of officer training, these groups of officers will form the battalion's leadership cadre, which will then be responsible for overseeing its own recruitment, training, and readiness of its enlisted men. It is hoped that having the Iraqi leadership train its own will overcome problems faced by CAATT's training process; namely recruitment, desertion, and unit loyalty.\n\n===Military Transition Teams===\nAll Iraqi Army battalions have embedded U.S. [[Military transition team]]s, according to the [[National Strategy for Victory in Iraq]]. The MiTTs advise their Iraqi battalions in the areas of intelligence, communications, fire support, logistics and infantry tactics. Larger scale operations are often done jointly with American battalions. This operational training aims to make the battalion self-sustainable tactically, operationally and logistically so that the battalion will be prepared to take over responsibility for battle space.\n\nThe DOD (as of March '07) reported that 6000 advisors arranged in 480+ teams were embedded with Iraqi units.<ref name=\"DOD 03/07\">U.S. Department of Defense, ''Measuring Stability and Security in Iraq (March 2007)'', p.&nbsp;23, p.&nbsp;25</ref> However, in April, the [[Congressional Research Service]] reported that only around 4000 U.S. forces were embedded with Iraqi units at a rate of 10 per battalion.<ref name=\"CRS 2007-04-27\" /> Former U.S. Army analyst [[Andrew Krepinevich]] argued that the roughly twelve advisors per Iraqi battalion (approximately 500 troops) is less than half the sufficient amount needed to efficiently implement the combat advisory effort .<ref>Andrew F. Krepinevich,  [http://www.csbaonline.org/4Publications/Archive/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers.pdf Send in the Advisers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927021806/http://www.csbaonline.org/4Publications/Archive/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }} - [[Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments]]</ref>  Krepinevich argues that officers try to avoid taking on advisory tasks due to the US Army's practice of prioritising the promotion of officers that have served with a U.S. unit over ones that have served with foreign forces.<ref name=FirstVN>PRWeb.com, [http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/7/prweb408426.htm First Vietnamese-American to Serve as a Military Advisor to the New Iraqi Army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071216194822/http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/7/prweb408426.htm |date=2007-12-16 }}, 2006</ref>\n\n==Current equipment==\n{{Main|List of current equipment of the Iraqi Army}}{{See also|List of former equipment of the Iraqi Army}}\n\n[[File:Iraqi KrAZ trucks.jpg|thumb|A convoy of 1st Motor Transport Regiment, 1st Iraqi Army Division [[KrAZ-6322]]]]\n\nVirtually all of the equipment used by the former Iraqi Army was either destroyed by the U.S. and British Forces during [[2003 invasion of Iraq|the invasion]], or was looted during the chaotic aftermath shortly after the fall of the Hussein regime. Four [[T-55]] tanks however have been recovered from an old army base in al-Muqdadiyah and are now in service with the [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st Division]].\n\nIn February 2004 the U.S. government announced that Nour USA was awarded a $327,485,798 contract to procure equipment for both the Iraqi Army and the Iraqi National Guard; however, this contract was canceled in March 2004 when an internal Army investigation (initiated due to complaints from losing bidders) revealed that Army procurement officers in Iraq were violating procedures with sloppy contract language and incomplete paperwork. On May of that same year the [[U.S. Army Tank-automotive and Armaments Command]] (TACOM) stated that they would award a contract worth $259,321,656 to ANHAM Joint Venture in exchange for procuring the necessary equipment (and providing its required training) for a minimum of 15 and a maximum of 35 battalions. The minimum bid would begin to be delivered immediately and further orders could be placed until the maximum of 35 battalion sets or September 2006 after the first order was fully delivered.\n\nIn May 2005, [[Hungary]] agreed to donate 77 [[T-72]]s to the Iraqi Army, with the refurbishment contract going to Defense Solutions to bring the tanks up to operational status for an estimated 4.5 million dollars US.<ref name=\"T72\">Defense Industry Daily, [http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraq-receives-t72s-bmps-with-another-armored-brigade-planned/index.php#more Iraq Receives T-72s & BMPs - With Another Armored Brigade Planned] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407065338/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraq-receives-t72s-bmps-with-another-armored-brigade-planned/index.php#more |date=2007-04-07 }}, 2005</ref> After a delay in the payment of funds from the Iraqi government,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraqs-t72s-payment-received/index.php|title=Iraq's T-72s: Payment Received|access-date=2007-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060404121918/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraqs-t72s-payment-received/index.php|archive-date=2006-04-04|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[9th Division (Iraq)|9th Mechanised Division]] received the tanks at its headquarters in [[Taji]] over a three-day period starting on November 8, 2005.<ref name=\"T72\" />\n\nOn July 29, 2005, the [[United Arab Emirates]] gained approval to purchase 180 [[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier|M113A1]] APCs in good condition from [[Switzerland]], with the intent to transfer them to Iraq as a gift. Domestic political opposition in Switzerland successfully froze the sale, fearing that the export would violate the country's longstanding tradition of neutrality as well as perhaps make Switzerland a target for terrorism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?F=1034590&C=europe|title=Defense News (dead)|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n173 [[M113]]s, 44 [[APC Talha]]s, and 100 [[FV103 Spartan]]s were donated by [[Jordan]], [[Pakistan]] and UAE. 600 [[AMZ Dzik]]-3 (''Ain Jaria'') APCs were ordered in [[Poland]] (option for 1,200) for delivery by Jan 2007. 573 [[Otokar Akrep]] APCs for delivery by Jan 2007. 756 [[Iraqi Light Armored Vehicle]]s (option for 1,050) for delivery by November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/bae-delivering-a-cougar-variant-for-iraqs-4454m-ilav-contract-02338/|title=Global MRAP: The International Light Armored Vehicle|access-date=2012-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019181156/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/bae-delivering-a-cougar-variant-for-iraqs-4454m-ilav-contract-02338/|archive-date=2012-10-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htarm/articles/20070415.aspx|title=Armor: Cougars Cousin Badger Arrives in Baghdad|website=www.strategypage.com|access-date=2012-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028164002/http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htarm/articles/20070415.aspx|archive-date=2012-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref>  Greece donated 100 [[BMP-1]] to the Iraqi Army.\n\n713 [[M1114]] and 400 [[M1151]] HMMWVs purchased for IA with delivery complete by end July 2006.\n\n[[Serbia]] has signed a US$230m deal with [[Iraq]] to sell weapons and military equipment, the defence ministry said in March 2008. It did not specify the weapons but Serbian military experts believe they include Serbian-made [[CZ-99]] hand guns, [[Zastava M21]] 5.56&nbsp;mm assault rifles, [[Zastava M84]] machine guns, anti-tank weapons ([[M79 Rocket Launcher|M79 \"Osa\"]], [[Bumbar]], and [[M90 Rocket Launcher|M90 \"Strsljen\"]]), ammunition and explosives and about 20 [[Utva Lasta|Lasta 95]] basic [[trainer aircraft]]. Iraq's defence Minister [[Qadir Obeidi|Abdul-Qadir al-Obaidi]] visited [[Belgrade]] in September and November to discuss boosting military ties with Serbia.<ref>[http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/25378 Serbia signs Iraq arms deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404133053/http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/25378 |date=2008-04-04 }} - IraqUpdates.com</ref><ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/28/europe/EU-GEN-Serbia-Iraq.php Serbia seals multimillion arms deal with Iraq] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211131353/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/28/europe/EU-GEN-Serbia-Iraq.php |date=2008-12-11 }} - International Herald Tribune</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, the United States proposed military sales to Iraq, which will include the latest upgraded [[M1A1 Abrams]] battle tanks, attack helicopters, [[Stryker]] armored vehicles, modern radios, all to be valued at an estimated $2.16 billion.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n| first = Christopher\n| last = Foss\n| url = http://www.janes.com/news/defence/land/idr/idr080812_1_n.shtml\n| title = Iraq orders Abrams tanks through US FMS programme\n| publisher = [[Jane's]]\n| date = 2008-08-12\n| accessdate = 2008-10-07\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080913003736/http://www.janes.com/news/defence/land/idr/idr080812_1_n.shtml\n| archive-date = 2008-09-13\n| url-status = live\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, the United States approved a $6 billion arms deal with Iraq that included 140 [[M1A1 Abrams]] tanks and 400 [[Stryker]] combat vehicles for elite Iraqi army units.<ref>[http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htproc/articles/20081218.aspx \"Procurement: Iraq Buys What It Knows\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530212034/http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htproc/articles/20081218.aspx |date=2013-05-30 }}, Strategy Page (December 18, 2008). Retrieved 20.02.2015</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, Ukraine has signed a deal to deliver $550 million worth of arms to Iraq, the agreement with the Iraqi ministry of defense calls for Ukraine to produce and deliver 420  [[BTR-4]] armored personnel carriers, six AN-32B military transport planes and other military hardware to Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.alsumaria.tv/news/19726/ukraine-to-sell-550-million-of-arms-to-iraq |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910233329/http://www.alsumaria.tv/news/19726/ukraine-to-sell-550-million-of-arms-to-iraq |archive-date=2014-09-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, the US military announced it had struck deals with Iraq that will see Baghdad spend $5 billion on American-made weapons, equipment and training.<ref>http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data/middleeast/2009/February/middleeast_February246.xml {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608205037/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2009%2FFebruary%2Fmiddleeast_February246.xml |date=2011-06-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Iraq finalized an order with [[Uralvagonzavod]] for 73 [[T-90|T-90S and SK tanks]]. The T-90SK is a command variant equipped additional radios and navigation equipment. As of 2018, 36 had been delivered and have been assigned to 35th Brigade of the [[9th Division (Iraq)|9th Armored Division]].\n\n===Uniforms and personal weapons===\nThe average Iraqi soldier is equipped with an assortment of uniforms ranging from the [[Desert Camouflage Uniform]], the 6 color \"Chocolate Chip\" [[Desert Battle Dress Uniform|DBDU]], the woodland-pattern [[Battle Dress Uniform|BDU]], the U.S. Marine Corps [[MARPAT]], or Jordanian [[KA7]]. Nearly all have a [[PASGT]] ballistic helmet, Generation I OTV [[ballistic vest]], and radio. Their light weapons consist of stocks of [[Cold War]]-era arms, namely the Tabuk series of [[Zastava M-70]] copies and derivatives like the [[Tabuk Sniper Rifle]], the Russian [[AKM]] and the Chinese [[Type 56 assault rifle]]s, the [[Zastava M72]] and [[PK machine gun|PKM]] machine guns, and [[Dragunov sniper rifle|Al-Kadesih sniper rifle]] though they have received assistance from the U.S. in the form of American-made weapons, including [[M16 rifle|M16A2]] and [[M16A4]] rifles and [[M4 carbine]]s.\n\nHowever weapons registration is poor. A 2006 report by the [[Special Inspector General for Iraq Reconstruction]] (SIGIR) notes that out of the 370,000 weapons turned over to the U.S. since the fall of Saddam's regime, only 12,000 serial numbers have been recorded.<ref>[http://www.sigir.mil/reports/quarterlyreports/default.aspx Reports to Congress] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222014506/http://www.sigir.mil/reports/quarterlyreports/Default.aspx |date=2010-02-22 }} - Special Inspector General For Iraq Reconstruction</ref> The lack of proper accounting for these weapons makes the acquisition of small arms by anti-governmental forces such as insurgents or sectarian militias much easier.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iraq}}\n* [[Iraqi Air Force]]\n* [[Iraqi Army Ranks Insignia]]\n* [[Iraqi Navy]]\n* [[Iraqi Republican Guard]]\n* [[Iraqi Security Forces]]\n* [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]]\n* [[Uniforms of Iraqi Armed Forces]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|first=Ibrahim |last=Al-Marashi |author2=Salama, Sammy|title=Iraq's Armed Forces: An Analytical History |url=https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma |url-access=registration |publisher=Routledge |location=Oxon and New York|year=2008 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma/page/254 254] |isbn=0-415-40078-3}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert|last=Lyman|series=Campaign|title=Iraq 1941: The Battles for Basra, Habbaniya, Fallujah and Baghdad|publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, New York|year=2006 |pages=96 |isbn=1-84176-991-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Pollack|2002}}|first=Kenneth M.|last=Pollack|title=Arabs at War: Military Effectiveness 1948-91|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|location=Lincoln and London|year=2002}} Also see Pollack's book reviewed in ''[[International Security]]'', Vol. 28, No. 2.\n\n==Further reading==\n* James Dobbins, Seth G. Jones, Keith Crane, Andrew Rathmell, Brett Steele, The UN's Role in Nation-Building: From the Congo to Iraq (CPA period)\n* {{cite book|author=Jessa Rose Dury-Agri, Omer Kassim, and Patrick Martin|title=IRAQI SECURITY FORCES AND POPULAR MOBILIZATION FORCES: ORDERS OF BATTLE|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Iraq%20-%20ISF%20PMF%20Orders%20of%20Battle_0_0.pdf|date=December 2017|publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]]|place=[[Washington DC.]]}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Embedded.html?id=iqR-6LOWcSYC&redir_esc=y|title=Embedded: A Marine Corps Adviser Inside the Iraqi Army|last=Gray|first=Wesley|date=2013-08-10|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=9781612514062|language=en}} Includes very useful thoughts on Iraq Army personnel 'laziness.'\n* Hamdani, Ra'ad. ''Before History Left Us''. Beirut: Arab Scientific Publishers, 2006.\n* [[International Crisis Group]], ''Loose Ends: Iraq's Security Forces between U.S. Drawdown and Withdrawal'' (Baghdad/Washington/Brussels: ICG, October 26, 2010).\n* [http://www.janes.com/news/security/jir/jir101104_1_n.shtml Michael Knights, \"Free rein: domestic security forces take over in Iraq,\" ''Jane's Intelligence Review'' (November 4, 2010)]\n* Tzvi Ofer, ''The Iraqi Army in the Yom Kippur War', transl. ''Hatzav'', Tel Aviv: Ma'arachot, 1986\n* Owen West, The Snake Eaters: Counterinsurgency Advisors in Combat\n* Kevin M. Woods, Williamson Murray, and Thomas Holaday, with Mounir Elkhamri, 'Saddam's War: An Iraqi military perspective of the Iran\u2013Iraq War,' McNair Papers 70, INSS/NDU, Washington DC, 2009.\n* [[imdbname:3074502|Michael Zacchea]] and Ted Kemp, ''[http://www.theraggededgebook.com/ The Ragged Edge: A US Marine's Account of Leading the Iraqi Army Fifth Battalion]''. [[Chicago Review Press]]. 2017. {{ISBN|9781613738443}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Army of Iraq}}\n* [http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-02-03/exclusive-iran-s-militias-are-taking-over-iraq-s-army Iran's Militias Are Taking Over Iraq's Army] (Feb. 2015), [[Eli Lake]], [[Bloomberg News]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140625235119/http://home.comcast.net/~djyae/site/?%2Fblog%2F Blog on Iraqi Forces by Former Naval Intelligence Officer D. J. Elliot]\n* [http://www.365iniraq.com/ www.365iniraq.com Articles and pictures from an Iraqi Army transition team]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217203623/http://www.access.gpo.gov/congress/house/pdf/109hrg/20923.pdf Building Iraqi security forces : hearing before the Subcommittee on National Security, Emerging Threats and International Relations of the Committee on Government Reform, House of Representatives, March 14, 2005]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/congress/2005_hr/050314-christoff.pdf Rebuilding Iraq: Resource, Security, Governance, Essential Services, and Oversight Issues: United States General Accounting Office Report to Congressional Committees, June, 2004]\n* [http://www.csis.org/media/csis/congress/ts050314cordesman.pdf Cordesman, Anthony H.: Prepared Statement before the Subcommittee on National Security, Emerging Threats, and International Relations of the Committee on Government Reform, March 14, 2005]\n* Cordesman, Anthony H., ''Iraqi Security Forces'', Praeger/CSIS, 2006 {{ISBN|0-275-98908-9}}\n* [http://www.csis.org/media/csis/pubs/060215_iraqforceupdate.pdf Cordesman, Anthony H., ''Iraqi Force Development: A Current Status Report July 2005 \u2013 February 2006'', February 15, 2006]\n* [http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0317/p06s03-woiq.html America's old Humvees add new luster to Iraqi fleet], ''Christian Science Monitor'', March 17, 2008\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140625235119/http://home.comcast.net/~djyae/site/?%2Fblog%2F Blog on Iraqi Forces by Former Naval Intelligence Officer D. J. Elliot]\n* [https://medium.com/war-is-boring/russias-bunker-smashing-rockets-have-arrived-in-iraq-5672b754870 Russia's Bunker-Smashing Rockets Have Arrived in Iraq]\n* khaleejtimes.com\n\n{{Iraqi security forces}}\n{{Armed Iraqi Groups in the Iraq War and the Iraq Civil War}}\n{{Iraq topics}}\n\n[[Category:Iraqi Army| ]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Iraq]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{update|date=October 2017}}\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Iraqi Army\n| native_name = \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0629 \n|image= Iraqi Ground Forces Emblem.svg\n|image_size= 160px\n|caption= Iraqi Ground Forces' insignia\n|start_date={{Start date|1921}}\n|active =\n|country= {{flag|Iraq}}\n|role= Ground-based military warfare\n|type= [[Army]]\n|size= Active: 54,000<ref>[[International Institute for Strategic Studies]], The Military Balance 2019, 344.</ref>\n|command_structure= [[Ministry of Defence (Iraq)|Iraqi Ministry of Defense]]\n|garrison= [[Baghdad]], Iraq\n|garrison_label=\n|motto=\n|march=\n|battles= '''First incarnation''':<br>[[Anglo-Iraqi War]]<br />[[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]]<br />[[First Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War]]<br />[[Six-Day War]]<br />[[Yom Kippur War]]<br />[[Second Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War]]<br />[[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]<br />[[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]<br />[[Iraq War]]<br />'''Second incarnation''':<br>Iraq War<br />[[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]<br />[[2017 Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]]<br />[[Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)]]<br />[[Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)]]<br />[[Military intervention against ISIL]]\n| anniversaries=January 6<ref>{{cite book|title=Iraq's Armed Forces: An Analytical History |url=https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma |url-access=registration |last=Al-Marashi |first=Ibrahim |author2=Sammy Salama |year=2008 |publisher=Routledge |location=London and New York |isbn=0-415-40078-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma/page/206 206]}} Al-Marashi and Salama note that the eighty-third anniversary of Iraqi Army Day was celebrated in 2004.</ref>\n| decorations=\n| nickname = \n| battle_honours=\n| disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1=\n| commander1_label=\n| commander2=\n| commander2_label=\n| notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol=\n| identification_symbol_label=\n| identification_symbol_2= [[File:Flag of the Iraqi Ground Forces.svg|border|100px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label= Flag\n}}\n\nThe '''Iraqi Army''', officially the '''Iraqi Ground Forces''' ([[Arabic]]: \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0629), is the ground force component of the [[Iraqi Armed Forces]], having been active in various incarnations throughout the 20th and 21st centuries. It was known as the '''Royal Iraqi Army''' up until the coup of July 1958.\n\nThe Iraqi Army in its modern form was first created by the [[United Kingdom]] during the [[Interwar period|inter-war period]] of ''de facto'' British control of [[Mandatory Iraq]]. Following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq by U.S. forces]] in 2003, the Iraqi Army was rebuilt along American lines with enormous amounts of U.S. military assistance at every level. Because of the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]] that began shortly after the invasion, the Iraqi Army was later designed to initially be a counter-insurgency force.<ref name=mssiaug06>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|title=Measuring Security and Stability in Iraq|work=U.S. Department of Defense|date=August 2006|page=52|access-date=2007-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911200618/http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|archive-date=2007-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://csis.org/files/publication/100422_GulfMilBal.pdf|title=The Gulf Military Balance in 2010|publisher=[[Center for Strategic and International Studies]]|date=22 April 2010|page=2|access-date=3 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809080759/http://csis.org/files/publication/100422_GulfMilBal.pdf|archive-date=9 August 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq|withdrawal of U.S. troops]] in 2010,  Iraqi forces have assumed full responsibility for their own security.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/15/iraq-withdrawal-us-troops_n_1012661.html|title=Iraq Withdrawal: U.S. Abandoning Plans To Keep Troops In Country|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=15 October 2011|access-date=24 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230100328/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/15/iraq-withdrawal-us-troops_n_1012661.html|archive-date=30 December 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' article suggested that, between 2004 and 2014, the U.S. had provided the Iraqi Army with $25 billion in training and equipment in addition to an even larger sum from the Iraqi treasury.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/world/middleeast/graft-hobbles-iraqs-military-in-fighting-isis.html?emc=edit_th_20141124&nl=todaysheadlines&nlid=68502098&_r=0|title=Graft Hobbles Iraq's Military In Fighting Isis|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 November 2014|access-date=22 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013223849/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/world/middleeast/graft-hobbles-iraqs-military-in-fighting-isis.html?emc=edit_th_20141124&nl=todaysheadlines&nlid=68502098&_r=0|archive-date=13 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Army extensively collaborated with Iraqi [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] during anti-ISIL operations.\n\n==History==\nThe threat of war with newly forming [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]], which claimed the Ottoman [[Mosul Province, Ottoman Empire|vilayet of Mosul]] as part of their country, led the British to form the Iraqi Army on 6 January 1921. The Mussa Al-Kadhum Brigade consisted of ex-Iraqi-Ottoman officers, whose barracks were located in [[Kadhimyah]].{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=149}} The United Kingdom provided support and training to the Iraqi Army and the Iraqi Air Force through a small military mission based in [[Baghdad]].<ref>Lyman, p. 25</ref> Iraqi Army Day celebrates the soldiers that fight for Iraq.\n\n===Royal Iraqi Army===\n{{Main|Kingdom of Iraq}}\nFrom 1533 to 1918, [[Ottoman Iraq|Iraq]] was under the rule of the [[Ottoman Empire]], and fought as part of the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire]]. After 1917, the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] took control of the country. The first Iraqi military forces established by the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] were the [[Iraq Levies]], several battalions of troops tasked to guard the [[Royal Air Force]] ([[RAF]]) bases from which the British controlled Iraq.\n\nIn August 1921, the British installed [[Hashemite]] [[King of Iraq|King]] [[Faisal I of Iraq|Faisal I]] as the client ruler of the [[Mandatory Iraq|British Mandate of Iraq]]. Faisal had been forced out as the [[King of Syria]] by the [[French Third Republic|French]]. Likewise, British authorities selected [[Sunni]] Arab elites from the region for appointments to government and ministry offices in Iraq. The British and the Iraqis formalized the relationship between the two nations with the [[Anglo-Iraqi Treaty|Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1922]]. With Faisal's ascension to the throne, the Iraqi Army became the Royal Iraqi Army (RIrA).\n\nIn 1922, the army totalled 3,618 men. This was well below the 6,000 men requested by the Iraqi monarchy and even less than the British set limit of 4,500. Unattractive salaries hindered early recruiting efforts. At this time, the United Kingdom maintained the right to levy local forces like the British-officered [[Iraq Levies]] which were under direct British control. With a strength of 4,984 men, the Iraq Levies outnumbered the army with its British set limit of 4,500 men.\n\nIn 1924, the army grew to 5,772 men and, by the following year, had grown still more to reach 7,500 men. It was to stay at 7,500 men until 1933. The force now had six infantry battalions, three cavalry regiments, two mountain regiments, and one field battery.<ref>Al-Marashi, pp. 23\u201324</ref>\n\nIn 1932, the [[Kingdom of Iraq]] was granted official independence. This was in accordance with the [[Anglo-Iraqi Treaty (1930)|Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1930]], whereby the [[United Kingdom]] would end its official mandate on the condition that the Iraqi government would allow British advisers to take part in government affairs, allow British military bases to remain, and a requirement that Iraq assist the United Kingdom in wartime.<ref>Ghareeb, Edmund A.; Dougherty, Beth K. ''Historical Dictionary of Iraq''. Lanham, Maryland and Oxford: The Scarecrow Press, Ltd., 2004. Pp. lvii.</ref>\n\nUpon achieving independence in 1932, political tensions arose over the continued British presence in Iraq, with Iraq's government and politicians split between those considered pro-British and those who were considered anti-British. The pro-British faction was represented by politicians such as [[Nuri as-Said]] who did not oppose a continued British presence. The anti-British faction was represented by politicians such as [[Rashid Ali al-Gaylani]] who demanded that remaining British influence in the country be removed.<ref name=\"Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lvii\">Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lvii</ref> In 1936, General [[Bakr Sidqi]], who had won a reputation from suppressing tribal revolts, was named Chief of the General Staff and successfully pressured the King to demand that the Cabinet resign.<ref>S.E. Finer, The Man on Horseback, 1962, 157-8.</ref> From that year to 1941, five coups by the RIrA occurred during each year led by the chief officers of the army against the government to pressure the government to concede to Army demands.<ref name=\"Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lvii\" />\n\n=== 1941 coup ===\n{{Main|1941 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat}}\nIn early April 1941, during [[World War II]], Rashid Ali al-Gaylani and members of the anti-British \"[[Golden Square (Iraq)|Golden Square]]\" launched a [[1941 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat|''coup d'\u00e9tat'' against the current government]].  [[List of Prime Ministers of Iraq|Prime Minister]] [[Taha al-Hashimi]] resigned and Rashid Ali al-Gaylani took his place as Prime Minister.  Rashid Ali also proclaimed himself chief of a \"National Defence Government.\"  He did not overthrow the monarchy, but installed a more compliant [[Regent]].  He also attempted to restrict the rights of the British which were granted them under the 1930 treaty.\n\nOn April 30 Iraqi Army units took the high ground to the south of [[RAF Habbaniya]]. An Iraqi envoy was sent to demand that no movements, either ground or air, were to take place from the base. The British refused the demand and then themselves demanded that the Iraqi units leave the area at once. In addition, the British landed forces at [[Basra]] and the Iraqis demanded that these forces be removed.\n\nAt 0500 hours on 2 May 1941, the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]] broke out between the British and Rashid Ali's new government when the British at [[RAF Habbaniya]] launched [[air strikes]] against the Iraqis. By this time, the army had grown significantly. It had four infantry divisions with some 60,000 men.<ref>Playfair, I.S.O.; and others (2006). The Mediterranean and Middle East, Volume II The Germans come to the help of their Ally (1941). History of the Second World War, United Kingdom Military Series, Official Campaign History, Naval & Military Press. {{ISBN|1-84734-427-5}}, p.182 and Lyman, ''Iraq 1941'', p. 25</ref> At full strength, each division had three brigades. The Iraqi [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st]] and [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Divisions]] were stationed in Baghdad. Also based within Baghdad was the Independent Mechanized Brigade comprising a [[L3/35]] light tank company, an [[Crossley Motors|armoured car company]], two battalions of [[motorized infantry|\"mechanized\" infantry]] transported in trucks, a \"mechanized\" machine-gun company, and a \"mechanized\" artillery brigade. The [[2nd Division (Iraq)|2nd Division]] was stationed in [[Kirkuk]], and the 4th Division was in [[Al Diwaniyah]], on the main rail line from Baghdad to Basra. All these \"mechanized\" infantry units were transported by trucks.\n\nHostilities between the British and the Iraqis lasted from 2 May to 30 May 1941. The German government despatched an aviation unit, [[Fliegerf\u00fchrer Irak]], and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] send limited assistance, but both were too late and far from adequate. In the end, the British were able to march on [[Baghdad]] and Rashid Ali al-Gaylani fled.\n\nAfter the Anglo-Iraqi War ended, Nuri as-Said returned as Prime Minister and dominated the politics of Iraq until the overthrow of the monarchy and his assassination in 1958. Nuri as-Said pursued a largely pro-[[Western world|western policy]] during this period.<ref>Ghareeb; Dougherty. Pp lviii</ref> The army was not disbanded. Instead, it was maintained to hinder possible German offensive actions launched from southern [[RSFSR|Russia]]. British troops left in the late 1940s.\n\n=== 1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War ===\nIn the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], the Iraqis deployed an expeditionary force which peaked at 15,000\u201318,000 men.{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=150, 156}} In 1948, the army deployed 21,000 men in twelve brigades and the [[Iraqi Air Force|Royal Iraqi Air Force]] deployed 100 planes, mostly British. Initially the Iraqis committed around 3,000<ref>D. Kurzman, ''Genesis 1948'', 1972, p. 382.</ref> men to the war effort including four infantry brigades, one armoured battalion and support personnel. These forces were to operate under Jordanian guidance<ref>I. Pappe, ''The Ethnic Cleansing of Palestine'', 2006, p. 129.</ref> During the first truce the Iraqis increased their force to about 10,000.<ref>Kurzman, p. 556.</ref> Ultimately, the Iraqi expeditionary force numbered around 15,000 to 18,000 men.{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=150}}\n\nThe first Iraqi forces to be deployed reached Jordan in April 1948 under the command of General [[Nur ad-Din Mahmud]]. On 15 May, Iraqi engineers built a [[pontoon bridge]] across the Jordan River and attacked the Israeli settlement of [[Gesher, Israel|Gesher]]. Over 3,000 Iraqi soldiers with armor and air support were unable to defeat less than 50 lightly armed Jewish defenders. Following this defeat Iraqi forces moved into the [[Nablus]]\u2013[[Jenin]]\u2013[[Tulkarm]] strategic triangle, where they suffered heavy casualties in the Israeli attack on Jenin which began on 3 June, but they managed to hold on to their positions. Active Iraqi involvement in the war effectively ended at this point.{{sfn|Pollack|2002|p=149\u2013155}}\n\nIn May 1955 the British finally withdrew from Iraq. The Iraqi authorities said during the withdrawal negotiations that a motorised infantry brigade was to be formed, based at the previous [[RAF Habbaniya]], a location that had been occupied by the British [[Iraq Levies]].<ref>Solomon (Sawa) Solomon, [http://www.edessa.com/history/solmn1.htm \"The Assyrian Levies, The Final Chapter\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722133011/http://www.edessa.com/history/solmn1.htm |date=2011-07-22 }}, ''Nineveh Magazine'' 4Q,93, V16, No4.</ref>\n\n===Republic declared===\n{{Main|Iraqi Republic (1958\u201368)}}\n\nThe [[Hashemite monarchy]] lasted until 1958, when it was overthrown through a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] by the Iraqi Army, known as the [[14 July Revolution]]. King [[Faisal II of Iraq]] along with members of the royal family were murdered. The coup brought [[Abd al-Karim Qasim]] to power. He withdrew from the [[Baghdad Pact]] and established friendly relations with the [[Soviet Union]].\n\nWhen Q\u0101sim distanced himself from [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Abd an-N\u0101sir]], he faced growing opposition from pro-Egypt officers in the Iraqi army. `Arif, who wanted closer cooperation with Egypt, was stripped of his responsibilities and thrown in prison. When the garrison in [[Mosul]] rebelled against Q\u0101sim's policies, he allowed the Kurdish leader [[Mustafa Barzani|Barz\u0101n\u012b]] to return from exile in the Soviet Union to help suppress the pro-N\u0101sir rebels.\n\nThe creation of the new Fifth Division, consisting of mechanized infantry, was announced on 6 January 1959, [[Army Day]].<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 'New Division for Iraq Army,' 7 January 1959</ref> Q\u0101sim was also promoted to the rank of general.\n\nIn 1961, an Army buildup close to [[Kuwait]] in conjunction with Iraqi claims over the small neighbouring state, led to a crisis with British military forces ([[British army|land]], [[Royal Navy|sea]], and [[Royal Air force|air]]) deployed to Kuwait for a period. In 1961, [[Kuwait]] gained independence from Britain and Iraq claimed sovereignty over Kuwait. As in the 1930s, Qasim based Iraq's claim on the assertion that Kuwait had been a district of the Ottoman province of Basra, unjustly severed by the British from the main body of Iraqi state when it had been created in the 1920s.<ref>Tripp, Charles. ''A History of Iraq''. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 2002, p.165</ref> Britain reacted strongly to Iraq's claim and sent troops to Kuwait to deter Iraq. Q\u0101sim was forced to back down and in October 1963, Iraq recognized the sovereignty of Kuwait.\n\nQ\u0101sim was assassinated in February 1963, when the [[Ba'ath Party]] [[February 1963 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat|took power]] under the leadership of General [[Ahmed Hasan al-Bakr]] ([[Prime Minister of Iraq|prime minister]]) and Colonel [[Abdul Salam Arif]] ([[President of Iraq|president]]). Nine months later `Abd as-Salam Muhammad `Arif led a successful coup against the Ba'ath government. On 13 April 1966, President Abdul Salam Arif died in a helicopter crash and was succeeded by his brother, General [[Abdul Rahman Arif]]. Following the [[Six-Day War]] of 1967, the Ba'ath Party felt strong enough to retake power (17 July 1968). Ahmad Hasan al-Bakr became president and chairman of the Revolutionary Command Council (RCC).\n\n===Six-Day War===\n[[File:Iraqi AML-60-20.jpg|thumb|Iraqi Army [[Panhard AML|Panhard AML-60]] armored car, 1970s. Iraq ordered about 250 of these vehicles between 1968 and 1976.]]\nDuring the Six-Day War, the Iraqi [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Armoured Division]] was deployed in eastern Jordan.<ref>Pollack, 2002, p.167</ref> However, the Israeli attack against the West Bank unfolded so quickly that the Iraqi force could not organise itself and reach the front before Jordan ceased fighting. Repeated Israeli airstrikes also held them up so that by the time they did reach the [[Jordan River]] the entire [[West Bank]] was in Israeli hands. During the course of the [[Jordanian campaign (1967)|Jordanian Campaign]] ten Iraqis were killed and 30 Iraqis were wounded, especially as the main battle was in Jerusalem. Fighting also raged in other areas of the West Bank, where Iraqi commandos and Jordanian soldiers defended their positions.<ref>Follow me- The story of the Six Day War 2. Six Day War- Tom Segev</ref>\n\nBarz\u0101n\u012b and the Kurds who had begun a rebellion in 1961 were still causing problems in 1969. The secretary-general of the Ba`th party, [[Saddam Hussein]], was given responsibility to find a solution. It was clear that it was impossible to defeat the Kurds by military means and in 1970 a political agreement was reached between the rebels and the Iraqi government.\n\nFollowing the Arab defeat in 1967, Jordan became a hotbed of Palestinian activity. During this time PLO elements attempted to create a Palestinian state within Jordan caused the Jordanians to launch their full military force against the PLO. As they were doing this Syria invaded Jordan and Iraq moved a brigade in Rihab, Jordan.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} Otherwise the only Iraqi activity was that they fired upon some Jordanian aircraft.\n\nIraq sent a 60,000 man expeditionary force to the Syrian front during the [[Yom Kippur War]]. It consisted of the 3rd and [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Armoured Divisions]], two infantry brigades, twelve artillery battalions, and a special forces brigade. The two armoured divisions were, Pollack says, 'unquestionably the best formations of the Iraqi Army.'(Pollack p.&nbsp;167) Yet during their operations on the Golan Heights, their performance was awful in virtually every category of military effectiveness. Military intelligence, initiative, and small unit independent action was virtually absent.<ref>Pollack p.173-5, citing among others Tzvi Ofer, 'The Iraqi Army in the Yom Kippur War,' transl. 'Hatzav,' Tel Aviv: Ma'arachot, 1986, p.128-65. Pollack notes that the various accounts of Iraqi operations on the Golan Heights are highly contradictory. He relies on Ofer, 1986, which is an Israeli General Staff critique of the official Iraqi General Staff analysis of the battle.</ref>\n\nAfter the war, Iraq started a major military build-up. Active duty manpower doubled, and so did number of divisions, from six to twelve, of which four were now armoured and two mechanised infantry. (Pollack p.&nbsp;182)\n\n===Iran\u2013Iraq war===\n{{see also|Order of battle during the Iran\u2013Iraq War}}\nLater, Saddam Hussein, looking to build fighting power against Iran soon after the outbreak of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]] doubled the size of the Iraqi army from 1981, when it numbered 200,000 soldiers in 12 divisions and 3 independent brigades, to 1985, when it had 500,000 men in 23 divisions and nine brigades. The first new divisions were created in 1981 when the 11th and 12th Border Guard Divisions were converted into infantry formations and the 14th Infantry Division was formed.<ref>Pollack 2002 p.&nbsp;207</ref> Yet the rise in number of divisions is misleading, because during the war Iraqi divisions abandoned a standard organisation with permanent ('organic') brigades assigned to each division. Instead division headquarters were assigned a mission or sector and then assigned brigades to carry out the task - up to eight to ten brigades on some occasions.<ref>Pollack 2002 p.&nbsp;208</ref>\n\nThe war came at a great cost in lives and economic damage - a half a million Iraqi and Iranian soldiers as well as civilians are believed to have died in the war with many more injured and wounded - but brought neither reparations nor change in borders. The conflict is often compared to [[World War I]],<ref>Abrahamian, Ervand, ''A History of Modern Iran'', Cambridge, 2008, p.171</ref> in that the tactics used closely mirrored those of the 1914\u20131918 war, including large scale [[trench warfare]], manned machine-gun posts, bayonet charges, use of [[barbed wire]] across trenches and on [[no-mans land]], [[human wave attacks]] by Iran, and Iraq's extensive use of [[chemical weapons]] (such as [[mustard gas]]) against Iranian [[troops]] and [[civilians]] as well as [[Halabja chemical attack|Iraqi Kurds]].\n\n===Invasion of Kuwait and the Persian Gulf War===\nBy the eve of the [[Invasion of Kuwait]] which led to the 1991 [[Persian Gulf War]], the army was estimated to number 1,000,000 men.<ref>Brassey's, [[IISS]] Military Balance 1989-90, p.101</ref> Just before the [[Persian Gulf War]] began, the force comprised 47 infantry divisions plus 9 armoured and mechanised divisions, grouped in 7 corps.<ref name=\"Michael Eisenstadt 1993, p.124\">Michael Eisenstadt, 'The Iraqi Armed Forces Two Years On, [[Jane's Intelligence Review]], March 1993, p.124</ref> This gave a total of about 56 army divisions, and total land force divisions reached 68 when the 12 [[Iraqi Republican Guard]] divisions were included.<ref>Eisenstadt notes that four IRG security divisions were formed between the invasion of Kuwait and the outbreak of war. They remained in Iraq during the war. Eisenstadt p.124</ref> Although it was said at the time in Western media{{Which|date=July 2018}} that Iraqi troops numbered approximately 545,000 (even 600,000) today some think<ref>Friedman, \"Desert Victory,\" USNI, 1992, 443, 446.</ref> that both the qualitative and quantitative descriptions of the Iraqi army at the time were exaggerated, as they included both temporary and auxiliary support elements. Many{{How many|date=July 2018}} of the Iraqi troops were also young, under-resourced and poorly trained [[conscript]]s. Saddam did not trust the army; among counterbalancing security forces was the [[Iraqi Popular Army]].\n\n[[File:Demolished vehicles line Highway 80 on 18 Apr 1991.jpg|thumb|left|Demolished Iraqi vehicles line the [[Highway of Death]] on 18 April 1991.]]\nThe wide range of suppliers of Iraqi equipment resulted in a lack of standardization in this large heterogeneous force. It additionally suffered from poor training and poor motivation. The majority of Iraqi armoured forces still used old Chinese [[Type 59 tank|Type 59s]] and [[Type 69]]s, Soviet-made [[T-55]]s & [[T-62]]s from the 1950s and 1960s, and some [[T-72]]s from the 1970s in 1991. These machines were not equipped with up-to-date equipment, such as [[thermal sight]]s or [[laser rangefinder]]s, and their effectiveness in modern combat was very limited. The Iraqis failed to find an effective countermeasure to the thermal sights and the [[kinetic energy round|sabot rounds]] used by the [[M1 Abrams]], [[Challenger 1 tank|Challenger 1]] and the other Coalition tanks. This equipment enabled Coalition M1A1s to effectively engage and destroy Iraqi tanks from well outside the distance (e.g. 8,200&nbsp;ft to Iraqi ranges of 6,600&nbsp;ft) that Iraqi tanks could engage.\n\nThe Iraqi tank crews used old, cheap steel [[Kinetic energy penetrator|penetrators]]{{Which|date=July 2018}} against the advanced [[Chobham Armour]] of these US and British tanks, with disastrous results{{Clarify|reason=What were the results?|date=July 2018}}. The Iraqi forces also failed to utilize the advantage that could be gained from using [[urban warfare]]&nbsp;\u2014 fighting within [[Kuwait City]]&nbsp;\u2014 which could have inflicted significant casualties on the attacking forces. Urban combat reduces the range at which fighting occurs and can negate some of the technological advantage that well equipped forces enjoy. Iraqis also tried to use [[Military doctrine#Russia and the Soviet Union|Soviet military doctrine]], but the implementation failed due to the lack of skill of their commanders and the preventive air strikes of the [[USAF]] and [[RAF]] on communication centers and bunkers.\n\nWhile the exact number of Iraqi combat casualties has yet to be firmly determined, sources agree that the losses were substantial. Immediate estimates said up to 100,000 Iraqis were killed. More recent estimates indicate that Iraq probably sustained between 20,000 and 35,000 fatalities, though other figures still maintain fatalities could have been as high as 200,000.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Robert Fisk, ''The Great War For Civilisation; The Conquest of the Middle East'' (Fourth Estate, 2005), p.853.</ref> A report commissioned by the U.S. Air Force, estimated 10,000-12,000 Iraqi combat deaths in the air campaign and as many as 10,000 casualties in the ground war.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Keaney |first=Thomas |author2=Eliot A. Cohen |title=Gulf War Air Power Survey |publisher=United States Dept. of the Air Force |year=1993 |location=|isbn=0-16-041950-6}}</ref> This analysis is based on Iraqi prisoner of war reports. It is known{{By whom|date=July 2018}} that between 20,000 and 200,000 Iraqi soldiers were killed. According to the Project on Defense Alternatives study,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0310rm8ap2.html|title=Wages of War - Appendix 2: Iraqi Combatant and Noncombatant Fatalities in the 1991 Gulf War<!-- Bot generated title -->|access-date=2009-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416233846/http://www.comw.org/pda/0310rm8ap2.html|archive-date=2009-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> 3,664 Iraqi civilians and between 20,000 and 26,000 military personnel were killed in the conflict. 75,000 Iraqi soldiers were wounded in the fighting.\n\n===During the 1990s===\nThe [[International Institute for Strategic Studies]] ([[IISS]]) estimated the army's composition immediately after the 1991 War as 6 'armoured'/'mechanised' divisions, 23 infantry divisions, 8 Republican Guard divisions and four Republican Guard internal security divisions.<ref>[[IISS]] Military Balance 1992-3</ref> [[Jane's Defence Weekly]] for 18 July 1992 stated that 10,000 troops from 5 divisions were fighting against Shia Muslims in the southern marshlands.\n\nThe IISS gave the Iraqi Army's force structure as of 1 July 1997 as seven Corps headquarters, six armoured or mechanised divisions, 12 infantry divisions, 6 RGF divisions, four [[Special Republican Guard]] Brigades, 10 commando, and two Special Forces Brigades.<ref name=IISS97>IISS Military Balance 1997-98</ref> It was estimated to number 350,000 personnel, including 100,000 recently recalled reservists.<ref name=IISS97 />\n\n===Invasion of 2003===\n\nIn the days leading up to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and the following [[Iraq War]], the army consisted of 375,000 troops, organized into five [[corps]]. In all, there were 11 [[infantry]] [[division (military)|divisions]], 3 [[mechanized infantry|mechanized]] divisions, and 3 [[division (military)#Armored divisions|armored divisions]].  The Republican Guard consisted of between 50,000 and 60,000 troops (although some sources indicate a strength of up to 80,000).\n\nIn January 2003, before the start of the invasion of Iraq in March 2003, the force was primarily located in eastern [[Iraq]]. The five corps were organised as follows:\n* [[1st Corps (Iraq)|1st Corps]], near [[Kirkuk]] consisted of the 5th Mechanized Division, 2nd Infantry Division, 8th Infantry Division and the 38th Infantry Division.\n* [[2nd Corps (Iraq)|2nd Corps]], near [[Diyala Governorate|Diyala]], had the 3rd Armored Division, 15th Infantry Division, and 34th Infantry Division.<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2003/iraq/forces/iraq/army/</ref>\n* [[3rd Corps (Iraq)|3rd Corps]], near [[An Nasiriyah]], had the 6th Armored Division, the 51st Mechanized Division, and the 11th Infantry Division.<ref name=MalMap />\n* [[4th Corps (Iraq)|4th Corps]], near [[Amarah]], included the [[10th Armored Division (Iraq)|10th Armored Division]], 14th Infantry Division and 18th Infantry Division.<ref name=MalMap>Malovany, \"Wars of Modern Babylon,\" pp. 662-663.</ref>\n* 5th Corps, near [[Mosul]], had the [[1st Mechanised Division (Iraq)|1st Mechanised Division]], and the [[4th Infantry Division (Iraq)|4th]], 7th, and 16th Infantry Divisions.\n* Western Desert Force, consisting of an [[Mechanized infantry|armored infantry]] division and other units in western Iraq.\n\nMalovany's description of deployments generally follows this pattern, A special headquarters was established on the eve of the war called the \"Great Day\" to command forces defending the Anbar district in west Iraq and the axes leading from it towards Baghdad.<ref name=MalMap />\n\nDuring the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] the Iraqi Army was defeated in a number of battles, including by [[Task Force Viking]] in the north, and the [[Battle of Nasiriyah]] and the [[Battle of Baghdad (2003)|Battle of Baghdad]]. The Iraqi Army was disbanded by [[Coalition Provisional Authority Order Number 2]] issued by U.S. Administrator of Iraq [[Paul Bremer]] on May 23, 2003 after its decisive defeat.<ref name=\"ISMFD\">Iraqi Security and Military Force Developments: A Chronology, 2, 4, 6, 7 [http://www.csis.org/media/csis/pubs/060330_securityforceschronology.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145310/http://www.csis.org/media/csis/pubs/060330_securityforceschronology.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }}</ref> Bremer said that it was not feasible to reconstitute the armed forces.  His justifications for the disbandment included postwar looting, which had destroyed all the bases; that the largely Shiite draftees of the army would not respond to a recall plea from their former commanders, who were primarily Sunnis, and that recalling the army would be a political disaster because to the vast majority of Iraqis it was a symbol of the old Baathist-led Sunni ascendancy...\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/06/opinion/06bremer.html?ex=1346817600&en=278710834dcd1971&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | work=The New York Times | title=How I Didn't Dismantle Iraq's Army | date=2007-09-06 | accessdate=2010-05-04 | first=L. Paul | last=Bremer III | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423154005/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/06/opinion/06bremer.html?ex=1346817600&en=278710834dcd1971&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | archive-date=2009-04-23 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Formations of the army, 1922\u20132003==\n\n===Corps===\n* [[1st Corps (Iraq)|1st Corps]] \u2013 established before Iran-Iraq War.\n* [[2nd Corps (Iraq)|2nd Corps]] \u2013 reorganised as an armoured corps for the 1991 [[Gulf War]], comprising the 17th Armoured Division and the 51st Mechanised Division\n* [[3rd Corps (Iraq)|3rd Corps]] \u2013 established before Iran-Iraq War. In 1978 reported to be headquartered at [[Nasariyah]] and to consist of 1st and 5th Mechanised Divisions and [[9th Armoured Division (Iraq)|9th Armoured Division]]. In 2003, Nasiriyah was the headquarters of the Iraqi Army's 3rd Corps, composed of the 11th ID, 51st Mech ID, and [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Armored Division]]\u2014all at around 50 percent strength. The 51st operated south covering the oilfields, and the 6th was north near [[Al Amarah]], which left three brigade-sized elements of the 11th ID to guard the An Nasiriyah area.<ref name=rohr>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mca-marines.org/GAZETTE/06rohr.asp |title=Fighting Through the Fog of War |publisher=Marine Corps Gazette |first=Karl |last=Rohr |accessdate=29 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201131311/http://www.mca-marines.org/Gazette/06rohr.asp |archivedate=December 1, 2008}}</ref>\n* 4th Corps \u2013 established 22 October 1981 to take over the northern sector of [[Khuzestan Province]], including Basitin, Shush, and Dezful sectors. Maj Gen Hisham Sahab al-Fakhri, previously 10th Armoured Division commander, was appointed as the corps commander. 1st Mechanised, 10th Armoured, and 14th Infantry Division were allocated to the corps, leaving 3rd Corps with 3rd and 9th Armoured, 5th Mechanised, and 11th Infantry Divisions.<ref>Malovany 168</ref>\n* 5th Corps\n* 6th Corps \u2013 Malovany 2017 writes that on 25 March 1985, an army meeting chaired by Saddam in Baghdad decided to transform the East Tigris Headquarters into a regular corps, the 6th Corps. It was to be reinforced with four additional divisions; as the 35th Division had been transferred to the 4th Corps, and the 32nd Division was with the East Tigris HQ, the new line-up would consist of the 32nd Division as before; the 12th Armoured Division and [[2nd Infantry Division (Iraq)|2nd Infantry Division]] transferred both from the 2nd Corps; the [[4th Infantry Division (Iraq)|4th Infantry Division]], and the 25th Infantry Division from the 4th Corps.<ref>Malovany 2017, 277.</ref> Malovany adds on the same page that during 1986 two more divisions joined the 6th Corps, an infantry division (\"apparently the 50th\") and the \"Marshes\" Division.\n* 7th Corps\n* Jihad Forces ([[Persian Gulf War]] of 1991)\n\n===Infantry and mechanised divisions===\n* [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st Division]], active from at least 1941. 1st Mechanised Division in [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]] and [[Iraq War]]. Reformed after 2003.\n* [[2nd Division (Iraq)|2nd Division]], active from at least 1941\n* [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Division]], active from at least 1941. Served in Iran\u2013Iraq War\n* [[4th Division (Iraq)|4th Division]], active from at least 1941. As 4th Mountain Infantry Division, served in Iran\u2013Iraq War.\n* [[5th Division (Iraq)|5th Division]], activated 1959. Served in Iran\u2013Iraq War. As 5th Mechanised Division, fought in [[Battle of Khafji]].\n* [[7th Division (Iraq)|7th Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War\n* [[8th Division (Iraq)|8th Division]]. As 8th Mountain Infantry Division, served in Iran\u2013Iraq War.\n* [[11th Division (Iraq)|11th Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]\n* [[14th Division (Iraq)|14th Division]]\n* [[15th Infantry Division (Iraq)|15th Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War ([[Operation Beit-ol-Moqaddas]])\n* 16th, 18th, 19th, 20th, 21st, 22nd, 23rd, 24th, 25th Divisions,\n* 26th, 27th,<ref>See Gulf War Air Power Survey, Vol. I, pg 68/97.</ref> 28th, 28th, 30th, 31st, 33rd, 34th, 36th, 37th, 38th Divisions\n* 39th, 42nd, 44th, 45th, 46th, 47th, 48th, 49th, 50th,\n* 51st Mechanised Division (surrendered during Iraqi Freedom 22 March 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/03/21/sprj.irq.division.surrender/index.html|title=CNN.com - Iraqi army division gives up fight - Mar. 22, 2003|website=edition.cnn.com|access-date=2018-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710075208/http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/03/21/sprj.irq.division.surrender/index.html|archive-date=2016-07-10|url-status=live}}</ref>)\n* 53rd, 54th, 56th Divisions\n* Eisenstadt reported 'about eight infantry divisions remain unaccounted for' as of March 1993.<ref name=\"Michael Eisenstadt 1993, p.124\" />\n\n===Armoured divisions up to 2003===\n* [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Armoured Division]], active by 1967, served in [[Yom Kippur War]], [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]\n* [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Armoured Division]], served in Yom Kippur War, Iran\u2013Iraq War\n* [[9th Armoured Division (Iraq)]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, disbanded after First Battle of Basrah/[[Operation Ramadan]], July 1982 (Pollack p.&nbsp;205). Reformed after 2003.\n* [[10th Division (Iraq)|10th Armoured Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, in [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]] with Jihad Forces (corps)\n* [[12th Division (Iraq)|12th Armoured Division]], served in Iran\u2013Iraq War, Persian Gulf War with Jihad Forces (corps)\n* [[17th Division (Iraq)|17th Armoured Division]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/17ad.htm|title=17th Armored Division|first=John|last=Pike|website=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=2010-08-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109182348/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/17ad.htm|archive-date=2009-01-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 52nd Armoured Division\n\n===Brigades===\nThe 65th Special Forces Brigade, 66th Special Forces Brigade, 68th Special Forces Brigade, and 440th Marine Brigade were active during the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]. (Eisenstadt)\n\n==Reform of the army==\n[[File:Iraqi T-72 tanks and an M113 APC from the Iraqi Army 9th Mechanized Division pass through a highway checkpoint in Mushahada, Iraq.jpg|thumb|right|Iraqi Asad Babil tanks and an M113 APC from the Iraqi Army 9th Mechanized Division pass through a highway checkpoint in Mushahada, Iraq.]]\nBased on Bush administration expectations that coalition forces would be welcomed as liberators after the overthrow of the Hussein regime,<ref>Christopher Spearin, 'A Justified Heaping of the Blame?,' in Stoker (ed). Military Advising and Assistance, Routledge, 2008, p.229</ref> prewar planners had only been expecting little if any resistance from the Iraqi people. Thus the new army was initially focused on external defence operations. The new Army was originally intended to comprise 27 battalions in three divisions numbering 40,000 soldiers in three years time. [[Vinnell Corporation]] was engaged to train the first nine battalions.<ref>Charles Tiefer, \"The Iraq Debacle: The Rise and Fall of Procurement-Aided Unilateralism as a Paradigm of Foreign War,\" University of Pennsylvania Journal of Int'l Law 29 (2007)</ref>\n\nThe [[Coalition Military Assistance Training Team]] (CMATT), headed by Major General [[Paul Eaton]], was the organization set up by the [[Department of Defense (United States)|Department of Defense]] with the responsibility of training and development of the new army. On August 2, 2003, the first battalion of new Iraqi Army recruits started a nine-week training course at a training base in [[Qaraqosh]]. They graduated on October 4, 2003.<ref name=\"CPA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpa-iraq.org/pressreleases/20031007_Oct-04-NIAGrad.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040701212721/http://www.cpa-iraq.org/pressreleases/20031007_Oct-04-NIAGrad.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-07-01|access-date=July 1, 2004|date=October 2003|title=CPA-IRAQ.org: Homepage of The New Iraq - Information about the Iraqi Dinar|website=www.cpa-iraq.org}}</ref>\n\nIn the interim, the new army had been formally established by [[Coalition Provisional Authority Order 22]] of August 7, 2003.\n\nIn April 2004, several Iraqi battalions refused to fight as part of the force engaged in the [[First Battle of Fallujah]].<ref name=\"West2011\">{{cite book|author=Bing West|title=No True Glory: A Frontline Account of the Battle for Fallujah|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SWaSHGkYEBoC|date=7 December 2011|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-80834-9|page=118|access-date=10 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012122337/https://books.google.com/books?id=SWaSHGkYEBoC|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Fifth Battalion was among the new Iraqi units that fought in Fallujah.<ref>* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9xF0DQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Zacchea+Kemp+The+Ragged+Edge&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7uu6YkrDVAhUFHJQKHXH3DGwQ6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q=Zacchea%20Kemp%20The%20Ragged%20Edge&f=false|title=Ragged Edge: A US Marine's Account of Leading the Iraqi Army Fifth Battalion|last=Zacchea|first=Michael|last2=Kemp|first2=Ted|date=2017-04-01|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781613738443|language=en|access-date=2017-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012122810/https://books.google.com/books?id=9xF0DQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Zacchea+Kemp+The+Ragged+Edge&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7uu6YkrDVAhUFHJQKHXH3DGwQ6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q=Zacchea%20Kemp%20The%20Ragged%20Edge&f=false|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2004, the CMATT was dissolved, and passed on its responsibilities to the [[Multi-National Security Transition Command \u2013 Iraq]] (MNSTC-I) (initially headed by Lt. Gen. [[David Petraeus]]) with the new focus on providing security for the Iraqi people from the emerging threat posed by the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/congress/2005_hr/050314-sepp.pdf |title=Prepared Statement before the House Subcommittee on National Security, Emerging Threats, and International Relations regarding the training of Iraqi Security Forces |author=[[Kalev Sepp]] |date=2005-03-14 |accessdate=2008-10-07 |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20050523220734/http://reform.house.gov/UploadedFiles/Sepp%20Testimony.pdf |archivedate=May 23, 2005 |format=PDF |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhile the regular army was being formed, U.S. commanders around the country needed additional troops more quickly, and thus the [[Iraqi Civil Defense Corps]] (which became the [[National Guard (Iraq)|Iraqi National Guard]] by July 2004)<ref name=\"Al-MarashiSalama2008\">{{cite book|author1=Ibrahim Al-Marashi|author2=Sammy Salama|title=Iraq's Armed Forces: An Analytical History|url=https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma|url-access=registration|date=7 April 2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-14564-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma/page/212 212]|access-date=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> was formed. Coalition commanders formed these militia-type units separately in each area; only later were they gradually brought together as one force. There were several instances where they have refused to take military action against fellow Iraqis, such as in [[Fallujah]], deserted, or allegedly aided the resistance. It is alleged that most guardsmen were drawn from the [[Shia]] majority in Southern Iraq or the [[Kurd]]ish majority in northern Iraq, rather than from the [[Sunni]] area which they were ordered to attack. In September 2004, a senior member of the National Guard, General Talib al-Lahibi was arrested on suspicion of having links with insurgent groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/3691540.stm|title=US arrests senior Iraqi commander|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331004205/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/3691540.stm|archive-date=31 March 2007|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In December 2004, it was announced that the Iraqi National Guard would be dissolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/4133039.stm|title=Iraq to dissolve National Guard|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228051413/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/4133039.stm|archive-date=28 February 2007|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At this time its strength was officially over 40,000 men. Its units became part of the army. The absorption of the ING by the regular army appears to have taken place on January 6, 2005, Iraqi Army Day.<ref>Cordesman and Baetjer, 2006, p.147-148. On the ING, see Neil Barnett, 'Iraq's turbulent transition,' [[Jane's Defence Weekly]], 8 September 2004, p.23</ref>\n\nOn August 14, 2004, the [[NATO Training Mission - Iraq]] was established to assist the Iraqi military, including the army. On September 20 the provisional Fallujah Brigade dissolved after being sent in to secure the city. The Fallujah Brigade experiment of using former insurgents to secure a city was not repeated.\n\nArmy training was transferred from [[Vinnell Corporation]] to the [[United States armed forces]] supported by U.S. allies, and is now done by three Iraqi training battalions. Training was impeded by domestic instability, infiltration by insurgents, and high desertion rates.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}} In June 2005, the partnership between Coalition forces and Iraqi forces has increased due to the growing number of battalions in the Iraqi army, which then stood around 115. Out of this number, it was deemed that 80 of them were able to carry out operations in the field with Coalition support limited to logistics and strategic planning, whilst another 20-30 battalions still needed major Coalition support to carry out their operations. As of October 5, 2005 the Iraqi Army had 90 battalions trained well enough to be \"deployed independently\", i.e. without the help of others such as the United States.<ref>The Long War Journal, [http://billroggio.com/archives/2005/10/training_the_ir_1.php Training the Iraqi Army - Revisited, Again] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070408181617/http://billroggio.com/archives/2005/10/training_the_ir_1.php |date=2007-04-08 }}, 2005</ref>\n\n[[File:Iraqi army 03 2011.jpg|thumb|Iraqi [[commandos]] training under the supervision of soldiers of the US [[82nd Airborne]].]]\nOn May 3, 2006 a significant command-and-control development took place. The Iraqi Army command and control center opened in a ceremony at the [[Iraqi Ground Forces Command]] (IFGC) headquarters at [[Camp Victory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Daily/May/060504.htm|title=Iraqi command and control center opens doors amidst turnover of new territory|date=2006-05-04|publisher=[[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708233659/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Daily/May/060504.htm|archivedate=2006-07-08}}</ref> The IGFC was established to exercise command and control of assigned Iraqi Army forces and, upon assuming Operational Control, to plan and direct operations to defeat the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]]. At the time, the IFGC was commanded by Lt. Gen. Abdul-Qadar. In 2006 the ten planned divisions began to be certified and assume battlespace responsibility: the 6th and 8th before June 26, 2006, the 9th on June 26, 2006, the 5th on July 3, 2006, the 4th on August 8, 2006, and the 2nd on December 21, 2006. After divisions were certified, they began to be transferred from U.S. operational control to Iraqi control of the IGFC. The 8th Division was transferred on September 7, 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/10359|title=US hands over control of Iraq military|date=7 September 2006|website=Iraq Updates|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116040104/http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/10359|archive-date=16 January 2009|url-status=dead|access-date=3 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2006/09/200849134437544335.html|title=US hands over control of Iraq military|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104192311/https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2006/09/200849134437544335.html|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> and the 3rd Division on December 1, 2006. Another unspecified division also was transferred to IGFC control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=2270|title=Iraqis to Command Four Northern Divisions by February, U.S. General Says|publisher=U.S. Department of defense|date=December 1, 2006|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130123733/http://www.defenselink.mil/news/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=2270|archive-date=30 November 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also transferred to the Iraqi [[chain of command]] were smaller logistics units: on November 1, 2006, the 5th Motor Transport Regiment (MTR) was the fifth of nine MTRs to be transferred to the Iraqi Army divisions. 2007 plans included, MNF-I said, great efforts to make the Iraqi Army able to sustain itself logistically.<ref>MTRs transferred in order of event: 8th, 4th, 6th, 5th and 1st (2 Nov). [http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7392&Itemid=109 IA 5th MTR driving toward success - Daily article on www.mnf-iraq.com, 20 November 2006.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929105112/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7392&Itemid=109 |date=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAs of June 26, 2006, three Iraqi divisions, 18 brigades and 69 battalions were in control of battlespace (including two police commando battalions).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/PentagonPresser/060623-casey-rumsfeld.htm|title=Pentagon Press Briefing June 23, 2006, with Secretary Donald Rumsfeld and Gen. George Casey|publisher=MNF-I|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112041117/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/PentagonPresser/060623-casey-rumsfeld.htm|archive-date=12 January 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\n[[File:080216 3-14 graduation.jpg|thumb|Members of Iraqi Army 3rd Brigade, [[14th Division (Iraq)|14th Division]] participate in a parade for Iraqi and Coalition military members attending the graduation ceremony, February 13.]]\n\nOn March 25, 2008, the Iraqi Army launched its first solely planned and executed high-profile division-level operation, [[Battle of Basra (2008)|Operation Charge of the Knights]] in Basra. They received [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]] support only in air support, logistics and via embedded advisors. Also, a British infantry brigade, part of [[Multi-National Division (South-East) (Iraq)|Multi-National Division South-East]], and stationed in Basra, were ready in a tactical overwatch role. Their participation was limited to the provision of embedded training teams.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nIn April\u2013June 2008, two brigades of the Iraqi Army 11th Division, supported by US forces, moved into the southern third of [[Sadr City]]. They were tasked to stop rocket and mortar attacks on US bases and the [[Green Zone]]. Following the [[Siege of Sadr City]]\u2014a month of fighting\u2014the [[Mahdi Army]] agreed to let Iraqi forces into the remaining portion of the city. On May 20, troops from the Iraqi Army 3rd Brigade of the [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st (Iraqi Reaction Force) Division]] and a brigade from the 9th Division moved into the northern districts of Sadr City and began clearing operations.\n\nIn May,  Iraqi army forces launched [[Operation Lion's Roar]] (later renamed to Operation Mother of Two Springs) in Mosul and surrounding areas of Nineveh Governorate. Iraq became one of the top purchasers of U.S. military equipment with the Iraqi army trading its [[AK-47]] assault rifles for the more accurate U.S. [[M16 rifle|M-16]] and [[M4 Carbine|M-4]] rifles, among other equipment.<ref>Ceerwan Aziz, [https://www.usatoday.com/news/military/2008-05-21-iraqarms_N.htm \"Iraqi forces load up on U.S. arms,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314035113/http://www.usatoday.com/news/military/2008-05-21-iraqarms_N.htm |date=2012-03-14}} ''USA Today'' (5/22/2008). Retrieved 11 October 2014</ref>\n\nIn June 2008 the army moved troops to the southern [[Maysan Governorate]]. Following a four-day amnesty for insurgents to turn over weapons, the Iraqi Army moved into the provincial capital Amarah.\n\n===2012===\nEach of the joint and multi-agency operational commands also include the [[Department of Border Enforcement]] (DBE), Federal Police, Emergency Police, Oil Police, FPS, etc. in their command as well as Iraqi Army.\n\nAs of the Fall of 2012, the Iraqi Army was organized as follows:\n* National Operations Center \u2013 [[Baghdad]]\n** Baghdad Operational Command \u2013 Baghdad<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage7-IGFC-B.pdf|title=Microsoft Word \u2013 OOBpage7-IGFC-B.rtf|access-date=2008-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145308/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage7-IGFC-B.pdf|archive-date=2008-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 Lt. Gen. [[Abud Qanbar]]\n*** Karkh Area Command (KAC) \u2013 Western Baghdad. Responsible for the Kadhimiyah, Karkh, Mansour, Bayaa, and Doura Security Districts.\n*** Rusafa Area Command (RAC) \u2013 Eastern Baghdad. Responsible for the Adhamiyah, Rusafa, Sadr City, New Baghdad, and Karadah Security Districts.\n*** [[6th Division (Iraq)|6th Motorised Division]] \u2013 Western Baghdad.\n*** [[9th Division (Iraq)|9th Armored Division]] \u2013 Taji \u2013 Division certified and assumes responsibility of the battle space of the northern [[Baghdad Governorate]] on June 26, 2006.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Publications/TWII/060626.pdf This Week in Iraq \u2013 MNF-I Newsletter] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060711234430/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/Publications/TWII/060626.pdf |date=2006-07-11}}, June 26, 2006</ref>\n*** [[11th Division (Iraq)|11th Infantry Division]] \u2013 East Baghdad (probably planned to become a mechanized division).\n*** [[17th Division (Iraq)|17th Commando Division]] \u2013 HQ [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmadiyah]] The 17th Division commander has been reported as Staff Maj. Gen. Ali Jassam Mohammad.\n*** 23rd Commando Brigade\n*** 25th Commando Brigade \u2013 'Baghdad Eagles' \u2013 former 4th Bde, 6th Div. Has received commando training by U.S. [[Special Forces]] and air assault training.\n*** 55th Commando Brigade\n** Niniweh Operational Command<ref>Long War Journal, [http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage5-IGFC-M.pdf Microsoft Word \u2013 OOBpage5-IGFC-M.rtf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145306/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage5-IGFC-M.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }}</ref> \u2013 Mosul\n*** [[2nd Division (Iraq)|2nd Division]] \u2013 [[Mosul]] destroyed by ISIS in 2014\n*** [[3rd Division (Iraq)|3rd Motorised Division]] \u2013 [[Al-Kasik]] destroyed by ISIS in 2014\n*** [[15th Infantry Division (Iraq)|15th Division]] Formed in 2015\n*** 16th Division\n** Diyala Operational Command \u2013 Sulamaniyah, Diyala, Kirkuk, Salahadin\n*** [[4th Division (Iraq)|4th Motorised Division]] \u2013 Tikrit \u2013 Division certified on August 8, 2006.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1894&Itemid=18 Daily story on MNF-I Webpage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913030540/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1894&Itemid=18 |date=2007-09-13}}, August 9, 2006</ref>\n*** [[5th Division (Iraq)|5th Infantry Division]] (Iron) \u2013 [[Diyala Governorate]] \u2013 Division certified on July 3, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mnstci.iraq.centcom.mil/docs/advisor/currentissue.pdf |title=The Advisor, MNSTC-I Newsletter, July 8, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112011941/http://www.mnstci.iraq.centcom.mil/docs/advisor/currentissue.pdf |archivedate=2006-11-12|format=PDF}}</ref>\n*** [[12th Division (Iraq)|12th Motorized Division]] \u2013 Tikrit \u2013 split off from 4 Div in mid-2008.\n** Basrah Operational Command \u2013 Basrah\n*** [[8th Division (Iraq)|8th Commando Division]] \u2013 HQ [[Diwaniyah]]\n*** [[10th Division (Iraq)|10th Commando Division]] \u2013 [[An Nasiriyah]]\n*** [[14th Division (Iraq)|14th Division]] \u2013 Basrah<ref>[http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage9-IAJoint%20forming.pdf Page 9: IGFC Basrah Sector] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145307/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage9-IAJoint%20forming.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }} - Long War Journal</ref> \u2013 division commander Maj. Gen. Abdul Aziz Noor Swady al Dalmy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mil/-news/2010/01/25/33467-iraqi-bedouins-seek-role-in-secure-future/|title=Iraqi Bedouins seek role in secure future|date=25 January 2010|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n** Anbar Operational Command \u2013 Ramadi\n*** [[File:\u0634\u0639\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0644 \u062a\u062f\u062e\u0644 \u0633\u0631\u064a\u0639 copy.jpg|25px]] [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st Infantry Division]] \u2013 Fallujah destroyed by ISIS in 2014\n*** [[7th Division (Iraq)|7th Infantry Division]] \u2013 Ramadi, West [[Al Anbar]] Province \u2013 transferred to Iraqi Ground Forces Command on November 1, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15012&Itemid=128|title=\"7th Iraqi Army Division now Controlled by Iraqi Government\", MNF-I Press Release November 03 2007|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132016===\nIn summer 2014, large elements of the Iraqi army were routed by a much smaller and less well-equipped force from the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].\n\nBudget problems continued to hinder the manning of combat support and combat service support units. The lack of soldiers entering boot camp is forcing Iraqi leaders at all levels to face the dual challenge of manning and training enabler units out of existing manpower. In the 2015 Pentagon budget, a further $1.3 billion has been requested to provide weapons for the Iraqi Army.<ref name=\"The New York Times\" /> However, the New York Times reported that \"some of the weaponry recently supplied by the army has already ended up on the black market and in the hands of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] fighters\". The same November 2014 article contended that corruption is endemic in the Iraqi Army. It quoted Col. Shaaban al-Obeidi of the internal security forces, who told the paper's David D Kirkpatrick: \"Corruption is everywhere.\" The article claimed that one Iraqi general is known as \"chicken guy\" because of his reputation for selling the soldiers' poultry provisions.<ref name=\"The New York Times\" />\n\nDivisions are forming engineer, logistics, mortar, and other units by identifying over-strength units, such as the Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR) battalions and other headquarters elements, and then transferring them as needed.\n\nProblems include infiltration and an insufficient US advisory effort. The new army aimed to exclude recruits that are former regime security and intelligence organizations members, personnel of the [[Special Republican Guard]], top-level Ba'ath Party members, and Ba'ath Party security and militia organizations.<ref name=\"New Iraqi Army NIA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/nia.htm|title=New Iraqi Army (NIA)|author=John Pike|accessdate=11 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006075831/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/nia.htm|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However the army is widely known to have been infiltrated by a multitude of groups ranging from local militias to foreign insurgents. This has led to highly publicized deaths and compromised operations.\n\nThe [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]] are a [[Ministry of Defence (Iraq)]] funded component that reports directly to the [[Prime Minister of Iraq]].<ref name=\"New Iraqi Army NIA\" />\nIn late June 2014, after the large-scale [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] offensive in the north of Iraq, it was reported that ISIL \"\"took the weapons stores of the 2nd and 3rd [Iraqi army] divisions in Mosul, the [[4th Division (Iraq)|4th division]] in Salah al Din, the [[12th Division (Iraq)|12th division]] in the areas near Kirkuk, and another division in Diyala (the [[5th Division (Iraq)|5th Division]]),\" said Jabbar Yawar, secretary-general of the Kurkish Ministry of Peshmerga Affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-iraq-isis-arms-20140629-story.html|title=ISIS weapons windfall may alter balance in Iraq, Syria conflicts|first=Raja|last=Abdulrahim|date=29 June 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065329/http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-iraq-isis-arms-20140629-story.html|archive-date=13 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nReuters reported that the [[5th Division (Iraq)]], located in [[Diyala Governorate]], was by October 2014 reporting to informal \"militias' chain of command,\" not to the Iraqi Army, according to several U.S. and coalition military officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/iraq-abadi/|title=Power failure in Iraq as militias outgun state|first=Ned|last=Parker|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2017-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024225300/http://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/iraq-abadi/|archive-date=2017-10-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA much later report from Small Wars Journal said that in \"..2013 and 2014 the 7th Division of the Iraqi Army, 99% Sunni, fought IS virtually alone, until it was almost completely destroyed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/the-iraqi-military-the-us-led-coalition-and-the-mosul-operation-the-risk-of-snatching-defea|title=The Iraqi Military, The US-led Coalition and the Mosul Operation: The Risk of Snatching Defeat from the Jaws of Victory \u2013 Small Wars Journal|website=smallwarsjournal.com|access-date=2017-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013124113/http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/the-iraqi-military-the-us-led-coalition-and-the-mosul-operation-the-risk-of-snatching-defea|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe October 2014 Reuters report quoted Lieutenant General [[John Michael Bednarek|Mick Bednarek]], Chief of the [[Office of Security Cooperation]], in Iraq from 2013 until July 2014, as estimating that \"the army has only five functioning divisions ... whose fighting readiness ranges between 60 and 65 percent.\"\n\nMichael Knights wrote in 2016 that the rebuilding from the mid-2014 disaster had been steady but \"very slow\". \"By January 2015 a fair number of brigades had been salvaged and a couple of new brigades were built but the overall frontline combat strength of the ISF was halved due to attrition in the manning of each brigade. [U]nits were weaker and many were too demoralized or lightly equipped to do more than hold in place. A year later, by January 2016, significant progress has been made in terms of available forces albeit largely by shuffling around personnel and raising around a dozen new and very small 1,000-strong brigades.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/The-future.pdf|title=The Future of Iraq's Armed Forces|last=Knights|first=Michael|publisher=Al-Bayan Center for Planning and Studies|year=March 2016|publication-place=Baghdad|pages=22|access-date=2017-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921164909/https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/The-future.pdf|archive-date=2017-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref> The new 15th and 16th Divisions have been identified, which appear to comprise some of the new brigades that Knights mentions, including the 71st, 72nd, 73rd, 75th, and 76th.\n\nThe Institute for the Study of War said in their 29 December 2014 situation report that \"..The [[19th Division (Iraq)|19th Division]] is a new military formation intended to include members from the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, and 12th IA divisions that melted away during the rapid advance of ISIS in June of 2014. This formation will almost certainly include volunteer fighters, most likely displaced persons from Mosul, who reside in refugee camps. The.. sectarian composition of the unit will be important to watch. The formation of the division was initially proposed by Defense Minister [[Khaled al-Obaidi]] on November 4, 2014 during a visit to Iraqi Kurdistan. During that visit he requested assistance from the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]] [with] basing the new division in Iraqi Kurdistan and giving the force responsibility for clearing Mosul.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/2015-1-1-2%20Situation%20Report.pdf|title=Iraq Situation Report: January 1-2, 2015|publisher=Institute for the Study of War|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230616/http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/2015-1-1-2%20Situation%20Report.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe Iraqi Army began the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]] with a force of four divisions. A fifth was formed in 1959. By the outbreak of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]], the force had grown to nine divisions. By 1990, with wartime expansion, the force had grown greatly to at least 56 divisions, making the Iraqi army the fourth largest army in the world and one of the strongest in the Middle East. After the defeat in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]] in 1991, force size dropped to around 23 divisions, as well as [[Iraqi Republican Guard|Republican Guard]] formations. The new army formed after 2003 was initially planned to be three divisions strong, but was then raised to ten divisions, and the force is now expected to grow to 20 divisions.\n\nThe U.S. [[House Armed Services Committee]] commented in 2007 that \"It is important to note that in the initial fielding plan, five army divisions would be tied to the regions from where they were recruited and the other five would be deployable throughout Iraq. This was partially due to the legacy of some army divisions being formed from the National Guard units and has caused some complications in terms of making these forces available for operations in all areas of Iraq, and the military becoming a truly national, non-sectarian force.\"<ref>[[House Armed Services Committee]], {{cite web|url=http://armedservices.house.gov/pdfs/OI_ISFreport062707/OI_Report_FINAL.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070627175546/http://armedservices.house.gov/pdfs/OI_ISFreport062707/OI_Report_FINAL.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 June 2007|title=THE CONTINUING CHALLENGE OF BUILDING THE IRAQI SECURITY FORCES (note 53, page 120)|format=PDF|date=27 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Department of Defense]] ''Measuring Safety and Security in Iraq'' report of August 2006, plans at that time called for the Iraqi Army to be built up to an approximately 300,000-person force. This was based around an Army with 10 infantry divisions and 6 mechanised infantry division consisting of 36 brigades and 113 battalions (91 infantry, 12 special forces, 24 mechanised infantry, 60 armored battalions, 1 security). Nine Motorized Transportation Regiments, 5 logistics battalions, 2 support battalions, 5 Regional Support Units (RSUs), and 91 Garrison Support Units (GSUs) are intended to provide logistics and support for each division, with Taji National Depot providing  depot-level maintenance and resupply. Each battalion, brigade, and division headquarters will be supported by a Headquarters and Service Company (HSC) providing logistical and maintenance support to its parent organisation. The army will also include 17 SIBs and a Special Operations Forces Brigade consisting of two special operational battalions.<ref name=\"MSSIAug06\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|title=United States Department of Defense|website=www.defenselink.mil|access-date=2007-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911200618/http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/Security-Stabilty-ReportAug29r1.pdf|archive-date=2007-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Iraqi tanks during the parade.jpg|thumb|left|Iraqi T-72s pass in review in Baghdad, June 30, 2009.]]\nThe Iraqi Army consists of nine regional joint commands. The Joint Operational Commands fall under the command of the National Operations Center.  The [[Iraqi Ground Forces Command]] does not directly command the army's divisions.\n\nAs of July 2009, the Iraqi Army had 14 divisions (1st-12th, 14th, and 17th, the designation 13 not being used), containing 56 brigades or 185 combat battalions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} The 6th Division and the 17th Division are still missing their fourth manoeuvre brigades. By April 2010, the combat battalion total had risen to 197 combat battalions.  Each division has four line brigades, an engineering regiment, and a support regiment.\n\nThree of the 56 brigades are not [[Iraqi Ground Forces Command]] combatant brigades and are not assigned to a division.  They are the [[Baghdad Brigade]] formed in the fall of 2008, the [[1st Presidential Brigade]] formed in January 2008, and the [[2nd Presidential Brigade]] formed in the spring of 2009.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n== Rank insignia ==\n{{main|Military ranks of Iraq}}\n\n==Training==\n[[File:Iraqi soldier with AKM.jpg|thumb|left|Iraqi soldiers perform a live-fire exercise using Bulgarian AR-M1 rifles.]]\n[[File:Female iraqi soldier with a Kalashnikov.JPEG|thumb|left|A [[Women in the military|female Iraqi soldier]] during live weapons training at the Jordanian Royal Military Academy.]]\n[[File:Iraqi T-72 tank fires.JPG|thumb|left|An Iraqi Army T-72 tank performs a live-fire training exercise at the [[Besmaya Range Complex|Besmaya Gunnery Range]], in Besmaya, Baghdad, 28 October 2008.]]\n\nThere are three levels of troop capability in the new army: one, two, and three. Level three refers to troops that have just completed basic training, level two refers to troops that are able to work with soldiers, and level one refers to troops that can work by themselves.\n\nMembers of [[NATO Training Mission \u2013 Iraq]] (NTM-I) opened a Joint Staff College in [[ar Rustamiyah]] in Baghdad on September 27, 2005 with 300 trainers. Training at bases in Norway, Italy, Jordan, Germany, and Egypt has also taken place and 16 NATO countries have allocated forces to the training effort.<ref>Jeremy M. Sharp and Christopher M. Blanchard - [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/mideast/RL32105.pdf Post-War Iraq:Foreign Contributions to Training, Peacekeeping, and Reconstruction] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924132513/http://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/mideast/RL32105.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }} - Congressional Research Service</ref>\n\nThe [[Multi-National Force Iraq]] has also conducted a variety of training programs for both enlisted soldiers and officers including training as [[medic]]s, [[engineer]]s, [[quartermaster]]s, and [[military police]].  Beyond the various courses and programs being held in-country, both American [[staff college]]s and [[military academy|military academies]] have begun taking Iraqi applicants, with Iraqi cadets being enrolled at both the [[United States Military Academy]] and the [[United States Air Force Academy|US Air Force Academy]].<ref>DJ Elliott and CJ Radin - [http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage3-JFC.pdf Iraqi Security Forces Order of Battle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227145309/http://www.longwarjournal.org/multimedia/OOBpage3-JFC.pdf |date=2008-02-27 }} - Long War Journal</ref>\n\n===Recruits and enlisted soldiers===\nIraqi Army recruits undergo a standard eight-week <ref name=\"CRS 2007-04-27\">Iraq - Post-Saddam Governance and Security, ''CRS Report for Congress'', p.41</ref> basic training course that includes basic soldiering skills, weapons marksmanship and individual tactics.  Former soldiers are eligible for an abbreviated three-week \"Direct Recruit Replacement Training\" course designed to replace regular basic training to be followed by more training once they have been assigned to a unit.\n\nSoldiers later go on to enroll in more specific advanced courses targeted for their respective fields.  This could involve going to the Military Intelligence School, the Signal School, the Bomb Disposal School, the Combat Arms Branch School, the Engineer School, and the Military Police School.\n\n===Officers===\nThe Iraqi Armed Service and Supply Institute located in [[Taji]] plays a significant role in training aspiring Iraqi [[non-commissioned officer]]s and [[commissioned officers]].  The training is based on a [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] model, chosen in part due to its shorter graduation time compared to [[United States Military Academy|West Point]]. Much of the Iraqi officer training programme is copied directly from the Sandhurst course.\n\nCMATT's main recruiting stations are located in [[Baghdad]], [[Basra]] and [[Mosul]]. The most desired recruits are individuals who have prior military service or are skilled in specific professions such as first aid, heavy equipment operation, food service and truck driving. A recruitment target of approximately one thousand soldiers is desired to eventually form a 757-man battalion.  Soldier fallout usually occurs due to voluntary withdrawal or failure to meet training standards.\n\nDue to the current demand for these battalions to become active as soon as possible, the first four battalions' officers, non-commissioned officers, and enlisted soldiers are being trained simultaneously (in separate groups). Notable differences in training between CAATT and former training under [[Saddam Hussein|Saddam]]'s regime include schooling in human rights, the laws of land warfare, and tolerance in a multi-ethnic team.\n\nBased on the philosophy used by the U.S. military to boost its own size in response to World War II \u2014 that an army can be built faster by focusing on the training on its leadership rather than enlisted soldiers \u2014 CMATT has pursued a similar strategy of focusing recruitment and training on commissioned and non-commissioned officers for the remaining 23 Iraqi battalions. Upon successful completion of officer training, these groups of officers will form the battalion's leadership cadre, which will then be responsible for overseeing its own recruitment, training, and readiness of its enlisted men. It is hoped that having the Iraqi leadership train its own will overcome problems faced by CAATT's training process; namely recruitment, desertion, and unit loyalty.\n\n===Military Transition Teams===\nAll Iraqi Army battalions have embedded U.S. [[Military transition team]]s, according to the [[National Strategy for Victory in Iraq]]. The MiTTs advise their Iraqi battalions in the areas of intelligence, communications, fire support, logistics and infantry tactics. Larger scale operations are often done jointly with American battalions. This operational training aims to make the battalion self-sustainable tactically, operationally and logistically so that the battalion will be prepared to take over responsibility for battle space.\n\nThe DOD (as of March '07) reported that 6000 advisors arranged in 480+ teams were embedded with Iraqi units.<ref name=\"DOD 03/07\">U.S. Department of Defense, ''Measuring Stability and Security in Iraq (March 2007)'', p.&nbsp;23, p.&nbsp;25</ref> However, in April, the [[Congressional Research Service]] reported that only around 4000 U.S. forces were embedded with Iraqi units at a rate of 10 per battalion.<ref name=\"CRS 2007-04-27\" /> Former U.S. Army analyst [[Andrew Krepinevich]] argued that the roughly twelve advisors per Iraqi battalion (approximately 500 troops) is less than half the sufficient amount needed to efficiently implement the combat advisory effort .<ref>Andrew F. Krepinevich,  [http://www.csbaonline.org/4Publications/Archive/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers.pdf Send in the Advisers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927021806/http://www.csbaonline.org/4Publications/Archive/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers/O.20060711.Send_In_The_Advisers.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }} - [[Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments]]</ref>  Krepinevich argues that officers try to avoid taking on advisory tasks due to the US Army's practice of prioritising the promotion of officers that have served with a U.S. unit over ones that have served with foreign forces.<ref name=FirstVN>PRWeb.com, [http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/7/prweb408426.htm First Vietnamese-American to Serve as a Military Advisor to the New Iraqi Army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071216194822/http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/7/prweb408426.htm |date=2007-12-16 }}, 2006</ref>\n\n==Current equipment==\n{{Main|List of current equipment of the Iraqi Army}}{{See also|List of former equipment of the Iraqi Army}}\n\n[[File:Iraqi KrAZ trucks.jpg|thumb|A convoy of 1st Motor Transport Regiment, 1st Iraqi Army Division [[KrAZ-6322]]]]\n\nVirtually all of the equipment used by the former Iraqi Army was either destroyed by the U.S. and British Forces during [[2003 invasion of Iraq|the invasion]], or was looted during the chaotic aftermath shortly after the fall of the Hussein regime. Four [[T-55]] tanks however have been recovered from an old army base in al-Muqdadiyah and are now in service with the [[1st Division (Iraq)|1st Division]].\n\nIn February 2004 the U.S. government announced that Nour USA was awarded a $327,485,798 contract to procure equipment for both the Iraqi Army and the Iraqi National Guard; however, this contract was canceled in March 2004 when an internal Army investigation (initiated due to complaints from losing bidders) revealed that Army procurement officers in Iraq were violating procedures with sloppy contract language and incomplete paperwork. On May of that same year the [[U.S. Army Tank-automotive and Armaments Command]] (TACOM) stated that they would award a contract worth $259,321,656 to ANHAM Joint Venture in exchange for procuring the necessary equipment (and providing its required training) for a minimum of 15 and a maximum of 35 battalions. The minimum bid would begin to be delivered immediately and further orders could be placed until the maximum of 35 battalion sets or September 2006 after the first order was fully delivered.\n\nIn May 2005, [[Hungary]] agreed to donate 77 [[T-72]]s to the Iraqi Army, with the refurbishment contract going to Defense Solutions to bring the tanks up to operational status for an estimated 4.5 million dollars US.<ref name=\"T72\">Defense Industry Daily, [http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraq-receives-t72s-bmps-with-another-armored-brigade-planned/index.php#more Iraq Receives T-72s & BMPs - With Another Armored Brigade Planned] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407065338/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraq-receives-t72s-bmps-with-another-armored-brigade-planned/index.php#more |date=2007-04-07 }}, 2005</ref> After a delay in the payment of funds from the Iraqi government,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraqs-t72s-payment-received/index.php|title=Iraq's T-72s: Payment Received|access-date=2007-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060404121918/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/2005/11/iraqs-t72s-payment-received/index.php|archive-date=2006-04-04|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[9th Division (Iraq)|9th Mechanised Division]] received the tanks at its headquarters in [[Taji]] over a three-day period starting on November 8, 2005.<ref name=\"T72\" />\n\nOn July 29, 2005, the [[United Arab Emirates]] gained approval to purchase 180 [[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier|M113A1]] APCs in good condition from [[Switzerland]], with the intent to transfer them to Iraq as a gift. Domestic political opposition in Switzerland successfully froze the sale, fearing that the export would violate the country's longstanding tradition of neutrality as well as perhaps make Switzerland a target for terrorism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?F=1034590&C=europe|title=Defense News (dead)|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n173 [[M113]]s, 44 [[APC Talha]]s, and 100 [[FV103 Spartan]]s were donated by [[Jordan]], [[Pakistan]] and UAE. 600 [[AMZ Dzik]]-3 (''Ain Jaria'') APCs were ordered in [[Poland]] (option for 1,200) for delivery by Jan 2007. 573 [[Otokar Akrep]] APCs for delivery by Jan 2007. 756 [[Iraqi Light Armored Vehicle]]s (option for 1,050) for delivery by November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/bae-delivering-a-cougar-variant-for-iraqs-4454m-ilav-contract-02338/|title=Global MRAP: The International Light Armored Vehicle|access-date=2012-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019181156/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/bae-delivering-a-cougar-variant-for-iraqs-4454m-ilav-contract-02338/|archive-date=2012-10-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htarm/articles/20070415.aspx|title=Armor: Cougars Cousin Badger Arrives in Baghdad|website=www.strategypage.com|access-date=2012-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028164002/http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htarm/articles/20070415.aspx|archive-date=2012-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref>  Greece donated 100 [[BMP-1]] to the Iraqi Army.\n\n713 [[M1114]] and 400 [[M1151]] HMMWVs purchased for IA with delivery complete by end July 2006.\n\n[[Serbia]] has signed a US$230m deal with [[Iraq]] to sell weapons and military equipment, the defence ministry said in March 2008. It did not specify the weapons but Serbian military experts believe they include Serbian-made [[CZ-99]] hand guns, [[Zastava M21]] 5.56&nbsp;mm assault rifles, [[Zastava M84]] machine guns, anti-tank weapons ([[M79 Rocket Launcher|M79 \"Osa\"]], [[Bumbar]], and [[M90 Rocket Launcher|M90 \"Strsljen\"]]), ammunition and explosives and about 20 [[Utva Lasta|Lasta 95]] basic [[trainer aircraft]]. Iraq's defence Minister [[Qadir Obeidi|Abdul-Qadir al-Obaidi]] visited [[Belgrade]] in September and November to discuss boosting military ties with Serbia.<ref>[http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/25378 Serbia signs Iraq arms deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404133053/http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/25378 |date=2008-04-04 }} - IraqUpdates.com</ref><ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/28/europe/EU-GEN-Serbia-Iraq.php Serbia seals multimillion arms deal with Iraq] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211131353/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/28/europe/EU-GEN-Serbia-Iraq.php |date=2008-12-11 }} - International Herald Tribune</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, the United States proposed military sales to Iraq, which will include the latest upgraded [[M1A1 Abrams]] battle tanks, attack helicopters, [[Stryker]] armored vehicles, modern radios, all to be valued at an estimated $2.16 billion.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n| first = Christopher\n| last = Foss\n| url = http://www.janes.com/news/defence/land/idr/idr080812_1_n.shtml\n| title = Iraq orders Abrams tanks through US FMS programme\n| publisher = [[Jane's]]\n| date = 2008-08-12\n| accessdate = 2008-10-07\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080913003736/http://www.janes.com/news/defence/land/idr/idr080812_1_n.shtml\n| archive-date = 2008-09-13\n| url-status = live\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, the United States approved a $6 billion arms deal with Iraq that included 140 [[M1A1 Abrams]] tanks and 400 [[Stryker]] combat vehicles for elite Iraqi army units.<ref>[http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htproc/articles/20081218.aspx \"Procurement: Iraq Buys What It Knows\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530212034/http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htproc/articles/20081218.aspx |date=2013-05-30 }}, Strategy Page (December 18, 2008). Retrieved 20.02.2015</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, Ukraine has signed a deal to deliver $550 million worth of arms to Iraq, the agreement with the Iraqi ministry of defense calls for Ukraine to produce and deliver 420  [[BTR-4]] armored personnel carriers, six AN-32B military transport planes and other military hardware to Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.alsumaria.tv/news/19726/ukraine-to-sell-550-million-of-arms-to-iraq |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910233329/http://www.alsumaria.tv/news/19726/ukraine-to-sell-550-million-of-arms-to-iraq |archive-date=2014-09-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, the US military announced it had struck deals with Iraq that will see Baghdad spend $5 billion on American-made weapons, equipment and training.<ref>http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data/middleeast/2009/February/middleeast_February246.xml {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608205037/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2009%2FFebruary%2Fmiddleeast_February246.xml |date=2011-06-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Iraq finalized an order with [[Uralvagonzavod]] for 73 [[T-90|T-90S and SK tanks]]. The T-90SK is a command variant equipped additional radios and navigation equipment. As of 2018, 36 had been delivered and have been assigned to 35th Brigade of the [[9th Division (Iraq)|9th Armored Division]].\n\n===Uniforms and personal weapons===\nThe average Iraqi soldier is equipped with an assortment of uniforms ranging from the [[Desert Camouflage Uniform]], the 6 color \"Chocolate Chip\" [[Desert Battle Dress Uniform|DBDU]], the woodland-pattern [[Battle Dress Uniform|BDU]], the U.S. Marine Corps [[MARPAT]], or Jordanian [[KA7]]. Nearly all have a [[PASGT]] ballistic helmet, Generation I OTV [[ballistic vest]], and radio. Their light weapons consist of stocks of [[Cold War]]-era arms, namely the Tabuk series of [[Zastava M-70]] copies and derivatives like the [[Tabuk Sniper Rifle]], the Russian [[AKM]] and the Chinese [[Type 56 assault rifle]]s, the [[Zastava M72]] and [[PK machine gun|PKM]] machine guns, and [[Dragunov sniper rifle|Al-Kadesih sniper rifle]] though they have received assistance from the U.S. in the form of American-made weapons, including [[M16 rifle|M16A2]] and [[M16A4]] rifles and [[M4 carbine]]s.\n\nHowever weapons registration is poor. A 2006 report by the [[Special Inspector General for Iraq Reconstruction]] (SIGIR) notes that out of the 370,000 weapons turned over to the U.S. since the fall of Saddam's regime, only 12,000 serial numbers have been recorded.<ref>[http://www.sigir.mil/reports/quarterlyreports/default.aspx Reports to Congress] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222014506/http://www.sigir.mil/reports/quarterlyreports/Default.aspx |date=2010-02-22 }} - Special Inspector General For Iraq Reconstruction</ref> The lack of proper accounting for these weapons makes the acquisition of small arms by anti-governmental forces such as insurgents or sectarian militias much easier.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iraq}}\n* [[Iraqi Air Force]]\n* [[Iraqi Army Ranks Insignia]]\n* [[Iraqi Navy]]\n* [[Iraqi Republican Guard]]\n* [[Iraqi Security Forces]]\n* [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]]\n* [[Uniforms of Iraqi Armed Forces]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|first=Ibrahim |last=Al-Marashi |author2=Salama, Sammy|title=Iraq's Armed Forces: An Analytical History |url=https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma |url-access=registration |publisher=Routledge |location=Oxon and New York|year=2008 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/iraqsarmedforces0000alma/page/254 254] |isbn=0-415-40078-3}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert|last=Lyman|series=Campaign|title=Iraq 1941: The Battles for Basra, Habbaniya, Fallujah and Baghdad|publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, New York|year=2006 |pages=96 |isbn=1-84176-991-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Pollack|2002}}|first=Kenneth M.|last=Pollack|title=Arabs at War: Military Effectiveness 1948-91|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|location=Lincoln and London|year=2002}} Also see Pollack's book reviewed in ''[[International Security]]'', Vol. 28, No. 2.\n\n==Further reading==\n* James Dobbins, Seth G. Jones, Keith Crane, Andrew Rathmell, Brett Steele, The UN's Role in Nation-Building: From the Congo to Iraq (CPA period)\n* {{cite book|author=Jessa Rose Dury-Agri, Omer Kassim, and Patrick Martin|title=IRAQI SECURITY FORCES AND POPULAR MOBILIZATION FORCES: ORDERS OF BATTLE|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Iraq%20-%20ISF%20PMF%20Orders%20of%20Battle_0_0.pdf|date=December 2017|publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]]|place=[[Washington DC.]]}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Embedded.html?id=iqR-6LOWcSYC&redir_esc=y|title=Embedded: A Marine Corps Adviser Inside the Iraqi Army|last=Gray|first=Wesley|date=2013-08-10|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=9781612514062|language=en}} Includes very useful thoughts on Iraq Army personnel 'laziness.'\n* Hamdani, Ra'ad. ''Before History Left Us''. Beirut: Arab Scientific Publishers, 2006.\n* [[International Crisis Group]], ''Loose Ends: Iraq's Security Forces between U.S. Drawdown and Withdrawal'' (Baghdad/Washington/Brussels: ICG, October 26, 2010).\n* [http://www.janes.com/news/security/jir/jir101104_1_n.shtml Michael Knights, \"Free rein: domestic security forces take over in Iraq,\" ''Jane's Intelligence Review'' (November 4, 2010)]\n* Tzvi Ofer, ''The Iraqi Army in the Yom Kippur War', transl. ''Hatzav'', Tel Aviv: Ma'arachot, 1986\n* Owen West, The Snake Eaters: Counterinsurgency Advisors in Combat\n* Kevin M. Woods, Williamson Murray, and Thomas Holaday, with Mounir Elkhamri, 'Saddam's War: An Iraqi military perspective of the Iran\u2013Iraq War,' McNair Papers 70, INSS/NDU, Washington DC, 2009.\n* [